column168: DRIVER GARY WILLIAMS, WITH TRACTOR 852 AND TRAILER PT93 WAS LOADED AT MERICHEM WITH 47 DRUMS OF CRESYLIC ACID FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE FAIRWAY WAREHOUSE AT THE PORT OF HOUSTON BARBOURS CUT TERMINAL. AFTER CHECKING INTO THE PORT, WILLIAMS SPOTTED THE TRAILER TO BE WAREHOUSE DOCK AS DIRECTED. THE DRUMS WERE UNLOADED BY A FAIRWAY FORKLIFT. AS THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR STARTED TO UNLOAD THE 45TH OF THE 47 DRUMS, THE DRUM WAS STRUCK AND A SMALL HOLE WAS CREATED. PRODUCT ALSO DRIPPED ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR OF THE DOCK AND WAREHOUSE. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN 1/2 GALL ON OF PRODUCT WAS LOST. THE PORT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS AND THE THE PORT POLICE WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. FAIRWAY CALLED IN RYDELL PETERSON ENVIRONMENTAL TO REMEDIATE THE AREA. THE LEAKING DRUM AND THE CONTAIMINATED ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUMS FOR RETURN TO MERICHEM FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. TWO PORT OF HOUSTON POLICE OFFICERS OBSERVING THE REMEDIATION ACTIVITIY WERE OVERCOME AND WERE HOSPITALIZED OVERNIGHT FOR OBSERVATION.
WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUNCTURED A DRUM WITH A FORK ON A FORKLIFT.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED BY OUR COMPANY FROM CENTRAL FREIGHT LINES ON SEPTEMBER 10, 1994, WITH A SCHEDULED DELIVERY AT SOUTHEASTERN FREIGHT LINES IN CONLEY, GA ON SEPTEMBER 12, 1994. THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED FIFTEEN, 5 GALLON CONTAINERS OF ORGANOPHOSPHHORUS PESTICIDES, LIQUID, TOXIC, N.O.S., 6.1, UN3018, II. ON SEPTEMBER 10, 1994, AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 CST, OUR DRIVER ELIZABETH PRICE STOPPED AT THE PILOT TRUCKSHOP IN RICHLAND, MS, AND NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING ABOVE THE TRAILER TIRES. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED OUR 24 HOUR SAFETY HOTLINE. AFTER THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED WE CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER (CHEMTREC) AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. AFTER THE TRAILER DOORS WERE OPENED, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A METAL POLE HAD PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF ONE OF THE 5 GALLON CANS CONTAINING ORGANOPHOSPHORUS PESTICIDES, LIQUID, TOXIC, N.O.S. A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY OR A SIMILAR ABSORBENT. A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE MATERIAL ALSO DRIPPED ONTO THE TRAILER TIRES; HOWEVER, I WAS INFORMED THAT NONE OF THE MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND. WE WERE INFORMED BY OFFICER JIM RUSSELL, WITH THE RICHLAND POLICE DEPARTMENT, THAT THE DAMAGED 5 GALLON CONTAINER WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL STILL IN IT WOULD BE TURNED OVER TO THE MISSISSIPPE STATE POLLUTION CONTROL BOARD. AT 1745 THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED AND CONTINUED ON TO HER DELIVERY. CENTRAL FREIGHT LINES HAS RECEIVED A FULL REPORT OF THE INCIDENT AND HAS MADE A COMMITMENT TO PROPERLY LOAD AND BLOCK AND BRACE ALL LOADS, IN ORDER TO ELIMINATE THE POSSIBILITY OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT FROM OCCURING IN THE FUTURE. WE FEEL CONFIDENT THAT THIS IS AN ISOLATED INCIDENT DUE TO THE NUMBER OF SHIPMENTS WE TRANSPORT FOR THIS SHIPPER. UP TO THIS POINT WE HAVE NOT HAD ANY RELEASES OR SPILLS OF ANY KIND.

THE DRIVER SAID THAT HE CHECKED THE CAP BEFORE HE LEFT THE PLANT. WHEN THE DRIVER RETURNED TO HIS TRUCK AT THE UNION 76 TRUCK STOP IN SLIDELL, LOUISANA FROM A BREAK, A SHERIFF TOLD HIM THAT HE HAD A LEAKING TANK. THE SHERIFF SECURED THE AREA, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM OF ST. TAMMANY PARISH WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. THEY HAD THE DRIVER PULL THE TRUCK OFF THE TRUCK STOP PROPERTY; NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL AND RELEASED THE DRIVER IN APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR. ESTIMATED LOSS 8 TO 16 OUNCES.

column168: TRAILER 375 ARRIVED AT OUR SOUTH DOCK AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 ON WEDNESDAY 9/21/94. AFTER THE DRIVER BACKED THE TRAILER IN TO THE DOCK DOOR, DOCKMEN OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AND IMMEDIATELY NOTICED A STRONG VINEGAR TYPE ODOR COMING OUT FROM THE FIRST HALF OF THE TRAILER. DOCK PERSONNEL IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT AS HAZARDOUS FROM THE SHIPPING PAPER. VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER REVEALED THAT THE DRUM HAD BEEN RAMMED BETWEEN SOME STANDING STEEL BAR FREIGHT AND SEVERAL PORTABLE TANKS. SEVERAL DOCK FOREMEN PUT ON PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (OV/AG RESPIRATORS, GOGGLES, HAZMAT SUITS) AND THEN LOADED THE LEAKING DRUM IN TO A 95 GALLON POLYETHYLENE OVERPACK; PERMISSION WAS GIVEN BY THE SHIPPER TO RETURN THE LEAKING DRUM TO THEM IN THE OVERPACK CONTAINER. THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL TANK WASH THAT IS LICENSED FOR HAZ/WASTE DISPOSAL. THE N&M TRAILER DRIVER WHO LOADED THIS MATERIAL WILL RECEIVE DISCIPLINARY ACTION FOR FAILURE TO PROPERLY LOAD AND SECURE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTAINER.

column168: THE COLUMBIA & COWLITZ RY. NIGHT SHIFT TRAIN CREW PULL UTLX 200524 FROM SOLVAY INTEROX PLANT AT 3500 INDUSTRIAL WAY PLANTSITE ON SEPT. 21, 1994 TO THE CLC YARD. THE DAY CREW THE NEXT DAY TOOK THE CAR TO WEYERHAUSER CHEMICAL PLANT AND LEFT IT TO BE WEIGHED PER INSTRUCTIONS FROM SOLVAY INTEROX. THE FOLLOWING DAY THE SAME CREW BROUGHT THE CAR BACK TO THEIR YARD. SUNDAY MORNING THE CLC EXTRA CREW WAS MAKING UP THEIR TRAIN AND WHEN THEY PICKED UP THE CAR IN QUESTION, UTLX 200524, THEY NOTICED LIQUID SPLASHING OUT THE TOP. TIME WAS 0815. THEY CALLED SOLVAY INTEROX RESPONSE TEAM WHO CAME PROMPLY TO ASSESS THE PROBLEM. THEY FOUND THE RUPTURE DISK OK BUT THE VENT STONE WAS SATURATED AND PRESSURE BUILT UP IN CAR. THEY RELEIVED THE PRESSURE AND CHANGED THE VENT STONE, WASHED DOWN THE CAR AND RELEASED THE CAR AT 1000 HOURS FOR US TO MOVE OUR INTERCHANGE POINT WITH THE BURLINGTON NORTHERN RAILROAD WHICH WE DID.

column168: J-M TRANSPORTS' TRUCK WAS MOVING WESTBOUND ON IL. HIGHWAY 71.  ANOTHER TRUCK, MOVING EASTBOUND APPROACHED IN THE WESTBOUND LANE.  IN ORDER TO AVOID A HEAD ON COLLISION, J-M TRANSPORTS TRUCK MOVED TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER.  THE TRUCK THEN SLID DOWN INTO THE DITCH CAUSING IT TO OVERTURN. DAMAGE TO THE LEFT SIDE OF J-M TRANSPORTS TRUCK PROVES THAT CONTACT WAS MADE WITH AN EASTBOUND TRUCK THE DAMAGE INCLUDED A BROKEN LEFT MIRROR. (FOUND IN WESTBOUND SHOULDER), DENTED LEFT FENDER, AND BROKEN REFLECTOR ON LEFT SIDE.  THE OTHER VEHICLE FLED THE SCENE.  J-M TRANSPORTS RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AT THE SCENE WITHIN 20 MINUTES OF BEING NOTIFIED OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE TEAM ASSISTED IN THE CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILLED FUEL AND PUMPED OUT THE REMAINING FUEL LEFT IN THE TRAILER.  IT IS FELT THAT THE DRIVER TOOK THE CORRECT ACTION IN AVOIDING A HEAD-ON COLLISION.  IN THE FUTURE, J-M TRANSPORTS WILL CONTINUE TO DEMAND THE SAFE-DRIVING PROCEDURES REQUIRED OF THEM.

(A & B) WARD TRANSPORT'S SEMI AND PUP TRAILERS WERE STRUCK BY A TRAIN AT A GRADE CROSSING.  THE REAR OF THE SEMI SEPARATED FROM THE FRONT HALF AND BOTH TRAILERS WERE DESTROYED.  WITNESSES AND OUR DRIVER REPORTED TRAFFIC WAS BACKED UP 20 TO 25 MINUTES AND THAT OTHER DRIVERS WERE GOING AROUND THE CROSSING BARRICADES.  OUR DRIVER STATED A TRAIN WAS STOPPED ON THE RAILS NEAREST HIM AND THAT TRAFFIC WAS GOING AROUND THE BARRICADES.  THE STOPPED TRAIN BLOCKED OUR DRIVERS VISION OF THE OTHER TRACKS UNTIL HE WAS CROSSING AND WHEN HE SAW THE OTHER TRAIN APPROACHING ON THE FAR TRACKS HE COULD ONLY GET ON THE THROTTLE AND ATTEMPT TO PULL HIS TRAILERS OFF THE CROSSING.  WITNESSES ALSO SAY CROSS GUARDS WERE MALFUNCTIONING.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CARIBE GENERAL ELECTRIC LOCATED AT CARR 129, KM 46.0 IN ARECHIO, PR TO RFE INDUSTRIES, INC.  LOCATED AT FOOT OF JERSEY AVENUE IN JERSEY CITY, NJ.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE, IN AN ATTEMPT TO PREVENT A COLLISION WITH A VEHICLE IN FRONT OF HIM WHO HAD MADE AN ABRUPT STOP, WAS FORCED TO MAKE A SUDDEN STOP.  IN DOING SO, THE DRIVER DIRECTED THE VEHICLE TO THE MEDIAN STOP.  IN DOING SO, THE DRIVER DIRECTED THE VEHICLE TO THE MEDIAN STRIP WHERE THE REAR TIRES BEGAN TO DIG INTO THE DIRT MEDIAN.  THIS CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO JACK KNIFE (PLEASE NOTE THAT THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR PROPERTY DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.)  THE VEHICLE WAS MOVED OFF THE ROAD AND WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN OPERATIONAL CONDITION.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SCENE, THE LOAD WAS CHECKED AND NO EVIDENCE OF A RELEASE WAS NOTED.  UPON ARRIVAL AT CLEAN HARBOR'S DEPTFORD SERVICE CENTER LOCATED IN DEPTFORD, NJ, THE DECISION WAS MADE TO TRANSFER THE CONTAINER ON THE TRAILER INTO A SECOND VEHICLE IN ORDER TO CONDUCT AN ADDITIONAL INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE.  DURING THE COURSE OF THIS TRANSFER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CONTAINER ON THE VEHICEL WAS PUNCTURED BY PALLET IT WAS ATTACHED TO RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 1/2 POUND OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY PLACED THE CUBIC YARD BAG INTO A CUBIC YARD FIBER BOX ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS.  THIS WAS THEN TRANSFERRED ONTO THE SECOND TRAILER AND CONTINUED ON TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE IS ATTRIBUTED TO A LOAD SHIFT CAUSED BY THE SUDDEN DECELERATION OF THE VEHICLE AND THE SUBSEQUENT JACK KNIFING OF THE VAN TRAILER.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO PREPARE EACH SHIPMENT IN FULL COMPLIANCE WITH ALL FEDERAL REGULATIONS IN ORDER TO MINIMIZE THE CHANCES OF A RELEASE IN THE EVENT A TRANSPORT VEHICLE IS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL, CT.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED AT MILE MARKER 32 ON I-480 WEST IN MACEDONIA, OH TO CONDUCT A ROUTINE LOAD AND TIRE CHECK.  DURING THIS STOP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED IN THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE TO IDENTIFY THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE AND TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  UPON ARRIVAL TO THE SCENE, THE CLEAN-UP CREW INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND DISCOVERED THAT THE DRUM APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN STRUCK BY A FORK-LIFT CAUSING A CREASE IN THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT ENROUTE, A PINHOLE LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE SITE OF THIS CREASE.  THE CREW THEN ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY, OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS IN THE SALVAGE DRUM FOR CONTINUINGTRANSPORTATION TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE LOADING PERSONNEL AT THE SHIPPERS LOCATION HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS DAMAGED DURING LOADING OR APPEARS NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL LOCATED AT ARMAND HAMMER BLVD. IN POTTSTOWN, PA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY AVE. IN CLEVELAND, OH.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED  IN CINNCINNATI, OH, PREPARATIONS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE CONTAINERS INTO A SECOND VAN TRAILER.  PRIOR TO MOVING THE VAN TRAILER, THE LOAD LOCK HAD BEEN REMOVED IN PREPARATION FOR TRANSFERRING THE CONTAINERS INTO THE SECOND VAN TRAILER.  WHEN THE EQUIPMENT OPERATOR APPLIED THE VEHICLE'S BRAKES AS HE APPROACHED THE LOADING DOCK, 5 CONTAINERS OVERTURNED CAUSING THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL IN TOTAL FROM THE CLOSURES OF THE DRUMS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE TRAILER INTO A CEMENT LINED CONTAINMENT AREA.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUMS.  ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUMS AND WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IDENTIFIED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT FOR DISPOSAL.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, THE EQUIPMENT OPERATOR HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED AS TO THE REQUIREMENTS FOR BLOCKING AND BRACING ALL CONTAINERS ON A VEHICLE WHENEVER A TRANSPORT VEHICLE IS MOVED.

A SWITCHMAN DETECTED THE ODOR OF AMMONIA WHILE WALKING PAST TANK CAR CITX 34414, RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUEFIED, 2.2, UN1005. INSPECTION OF THE FITTINGS INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON THE TANK CAR REVEALED THAT VAPOR WAS LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS 25 PSI, INDICATING THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS MALFUNCTIONING.  THE CONSIGNEE DISPATCHED RESPONDERS WHO REPLACED THE "O" RINGS IN THE UPPER SAFETY RELIEF VALVE ASSEMBLY, STOPPING THE LEAK AT 2337 ON 09/06/94.  AFTER ANOTHER INSPECTION ON THE FOLLOWING MORNING, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

AT A TRAIN MEETING POINT, THE CREW OF THE STANDING TRAINING TRAIN DETECTED THE STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM A CAR OR CARS IN THE TRAIN BEING MET.  THE MOVING TRAIN WAS STOPPED AND AN INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TANK CAR ACFX 17134, AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, 2.2. UN1005, WAS EMITTING VAPORS FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  RAILROAD EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  INSPECTION OF THE FITTINGS INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING REVEALED THAT THE A-END LIQUID EDUCATION VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN AND THERE WAS LEAKAGE AROUND THE PACKING GLAND.  AFTER VALVE WAS PROPERLY CLOSED, THE LEAKING STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE AN ADJACENT TANK CAR, ACFX 17134, THAT HAD BEEN LEAKING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, THE STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA WAS DETECTED AROUND TANK CAR NDYX 35218, AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, 2.2, UN1005. A CLOSE INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM THE SEAL BETWEEN THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  THE LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED.  THE LADING WAS TRANSFERRED TO FOUR CARGO TANKS AND THE TANK CAR PURGED BEFORE RELEASING IT FOR MOVEMENT TO A TANK CAR SHOP FOR REPAIR.

WHEN REPORTED WE EMPTIED THE TRAILER IN SEARCH OF THE CONTAINER.  WHEN FOUND WE IMMEDIATED PUT IT IN SALVAGE DRUM.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN CLEANED UP BY SPREADING CORN COB ABSORBANT AND SWEEPING IT UP.  THE CONTAINMENT WAS CLEANED UP ALSO WITH THE SAUIE MATERIAL.  ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED & PUT IN DRUMS.

THIS PAIL WAS HAND LOADED ONTO PEDDLE UNIT BY BR DOCKMAN... AT WHICH POINT IT WAS NOT LEAKING OR DAMAGED.  SOMETIME LATER THE DRIVER WHO WAS TAKING THAT UNIT OUT NOTICED AN ODOR IN THIS TRAILER & FOUND THIS PAIL JUST SLIGHTLY HIT BY SOME OBJECT & DENTED IN IMMEDIATELY UNDER LID.  THE LABEL ON THE FREIGHT SHOWED SEVERAL RIVULETS OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT & RAN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE PAIL.  IT WAS APPARENTLY DAMAGED WHILE SOMEONE HERE AT BR WAS LOADING OTHER FREIGHT ONTO THE PEDDLE UNIT.  HAVE SECURED RETURN AUTHORITY TO SHIPPER FOR CREDIT & INSPECTION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON I-74 AT THE 17 MILE MARKER WHEN HE FELL ASLEEP.  (WE BELIEVE) HE WENT GRADUALLY OFF THE ROAD & BURM & THEN NOTICED OR AWOKEN.  HE JERKED THE WHEEL BACK TO THE LEFT CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO BECOME UNBALANCED AND THE FORWARD MOTION OF THE LOAD TURNED THE VEHICLE ON ITS RIGHT SIDE WHERE IT SLID FOR 280 FT.  RUBBING THE SIDES AGAINST THE ROADWAY UNTIL HOLES WERE WORN IN THE SIDES OF ALL 4 COMPARTMENTS.  FINALLY COMING TO A REST WITH FIST SIZE HOLES IN ALL 4 COMPARTMENTS.  WE ESTIMATE IT TOOK 15 MINUTES OR LESS TO EMPTY OUT ALL THE LOAD EXCEPT 200 GALLONS IN COMPARTMENT #4.  7600 OF THE 7800 GALLONS OF DENATURED ETHANOL WENT IMMEDIATELY INTO THE DITCH FROM THE HOLES  IN EACH COMPARTMENT.  SPARKS (IF ANY) DID NOT IGNITE THE ALCOHOL.  OURS WAS THE ONLY VEHICLE INVOLVED. TRACTOR & TRANSPORT TRAILER AND 7600 GALLONS OF ETHANOL WERE A TOTAL LOSS TO CARRIER DRIVER WAS NOT HARMED AT ALL.  HE WAS FIRED FOR FAILURE TO KEEP CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE.  PAVEMENT WAS DRY AND OUR VEHICLE WAS IN PROPER CONDITION.  DRIVER HOURS OF SERVICE WAS NOT THE PROBLEM EITHER.  HE WENT ON DUTY AT 6:30 PM ON 9-22-94 & THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED AT 1:00 AM ON 9-23-94.  HE HAD HIS PROPER BREAK FROM  6:30 AM 9-22-94 TO 6:30 PM 9-22-94. (CLEANUP)

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 4, 1994, CHICAGO CENTRAL & PACIFIC TRAIN 51-03, WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND WHEN TWO ENGINES AND 11 CARS DERAILED AT MILE POST 435.2, NEAR THE UNINCORPORATED TOWN OF BOYER, IOWA.  AS A RESULT OF THE DERALMENT TANK CAR GATX 57061 WAS STRUCK BY ANOTHER RAILCAR PUNCTURING THE LEADING END (B) AT APPROXIMATELY MID LEVEL.  APPROXIMATLEY 16000 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT SPILLED OUT DUE TO THE DERAILMENT DAMAGE.  LOCAL INCIDENT COMMANDER EVACUATED THE 30 RESIDENTS OF BOYER WHICH WAS LOCATED ONE QUARTER OF A MILE TO THE WEST.  DUE TO THE FACT THAT PRODUCT DIDN'T ENTER A NEARBY WATER SOURCE SECONDARY MITIGATION CONDUCTED WAS TO ROPE OFF AREA OF LAND SPILL TO KEEP MEN AND EQUIPMENT THAT WERE RERAILING OUT OF THERE. THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED WITH WEDGES AND PACKING TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER SPILLAGE.  CAUSE OF DERAILMENT IS UNDETERMINED AS OF THIS WRITING.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM DIXIE CHEMICAL COMPANY LOCATED AT 10701 BAY AREA BOULEVARD IN PASADENA, TEXAS, TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INCORPORTATED LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OHIO.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED TO CONDUCT A ROUTINE TIRE AND LOAD CHECK.  DURING HIS INSPECTION, THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL DRIP COMING FORM THE BACK OF THE VAN TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER, WHO IN TURN, DISPATCHED ANOTHER DRIVER TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST IN THE CLEANUP OF THE RELEASE.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE SECOND DIRVER, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED, AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  PLEASE NOTE THAT IT IS ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN A PINT OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE VEHICLE ONTO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY.  CLEAN HARBORS PERSONNEL ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDIDRY AND OVERPACKED THA DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH ALL CLEANUP RESIDUE, WHICH WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THRU THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEDPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED, AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STURCTURALLY SOUND.

THE DAMAGE TO THE METAL PAIL WAS CAUSED BY THE PLACING OF A HEAVY SKID OF FREIGHT ON TOP OF THE METAL PAILS IN THE SHIPMENT.  THE CONSTANT HEAVY WEIGHT DURING TRANSIT CAUSED ONE OF THE PAILS TO BECOME CRUSHED AT THE TOP RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 32 OUNCES OF MATERIAL.  MATERIAL RECOUPED INTO ANOTHER 5-GALLON PAIL.  THIS DAMAGE COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED BY THE FREIGHT LOADER USING SOME COMMON SENSE AND NOT PLACING THE HEAVIER SKID OF FREIGHT ON TOP OF THE PAILS.

column168: DRIVER NOTICED ODOR COMING FROM TRAILER HE WAS PULLING AND NOTIFIED ROAD DISPATCH AFTER PAPERWORK WAS CHECKED HE WAS ADVISED TO OPEN DOOR TO TRY AND LOCATE CAUSE OF ODOR. column168: DOCK MAN WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING FREIGHT WITH A FORKLIFT WHEN HE NOTICED GRANGULAR LEAKAGE FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE SKID.  APARENTLY SEVERAL BAGS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT AT THE LOADING TERMINAL WITH A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF RECOUPING OF THE FREIGHT.  DURING TRANSIT SOME OF THE BAGS SHIFTED ON THE PALLETS AND BECAME TORN RELEASING SOME OF THE GRANULAR MATERIAL.  BAGS RECOUPED AND SENT ON TO DESTINATION.  DOCK PERSONNEL MUST PRACTICE PROPER LOADING AND BLOCKING TO PREVENT DAMAGE IN TRANSIT.  THE THIN PLASTIC BAGS DO NOT HOLD UP TO NORMAL FREIGHT HANDLING.

SKID OF BAGGED FREIGHT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED ACROSS DOCK WHEN ONE OF THE BAGS SLID OFF AND HIT THE CONCRETE FLOOR.  THE IMPACT TORE THE BAG WHICH CAUSED SOME OF THE GRANULAR MATERIAL INSIDE THE BAG TO SPILL OUT. MATERIAL RECOUPED INTO A CARTON AND FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.  THE PLASTIC BAGS ARE NOT SUBSTANTIAL ENOUGH TO ENDURE NORMAL FREIGHT HANDLING. SUGGEST THE BAGS BE MADE OUT OF TOUGHER MATERIAL.

column168: A CAR INSPECTOR DISCOVERED A DAMAGED DOOR ON CONTAINER CASU 70390 CONTAINING 68 DRUMS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLID, 8, UN1823, PGII. THE CAR ON WHICH THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WAS SET TO THE REPAIR TRACK WHERE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF LADING HAD BEEN RELEASED. WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING AND THAT ONE DRUM WAS OPEN AND THREE OTHERS WERE EXTENSIVELY DAMAGED. THOSE FOUR DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED, ALL DRUMS WERE CLEANED AND TRANSFERED TO TRAILER BNZ 235005, AND THE LOAD WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

PRIOR TO LOADING, THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES WERE NO CLOSED. PRELOAD STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE HAS BEEN REVIEWED WITH THE DRIVER. ALL RELEASED MATERIAL, ABSORBANT AND UNDERLYING GRAVEL WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA AND CONTAINERIZED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: DRIVER WAS DETAINED AT THE HUBBARD, OHIO SCALE FOR A D.O.T. COMMERCIAL VEHICLE INSPECTION. WHEN THE INSPECTION OFFICER OPENED THE DOOR ON THE TRAILER HE NOTICED A STRONG CHEMICAL SMELL AND INVESTIGATED THE ORIGIN. HE FOUND A WET SPOT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR APPROXIMATELY 2" - 3" IN DIAMETER AND DETERMINED THAT THE LOAD WAS TO BE CHECKED FOR LEAKING CONTAINERS. HUBBARD, OHIO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO INVESTIGATE, UNLOAD, AND OVER PACK 4 DRUMS INTO RECOVERY DRUMS. AFTER DECONTAMINATION CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED, DRIVER WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON TRIP. LOAD DELIVERED 9/29/94 A.M. THE MATTER HAS BEEN ADDRESSED WITH DRIVER, SHIPPER, CONSIGNEE AND SAFETY DEPARTMENT OF TRUCKING COMPANY THAT THIS PRODUCT WILL NOT BE SHIPPED IN THIS FASHION EVER AGAIN.

column168: TANKS WERE PICKED UP IN CROWLEY, LA.  FOR TRANSPORT TO GALVESTON, TEXAS. NO FAILURE WAS NOTED AT SHIPPING POINT.  WHEN AN UNKNOWN DRIVER FLASHED HIS LIGHTS AT THE TRUCK DRIVER.  HE LOOKED INTO HIS SIDE VIEW AND NOTICED FLUID LEAKING FROM TRUCK.  HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER PARKING HIS VEHICLE AT AN ANGLE THAT WOULD PREVENT ALL OF THE LIQUID FROM LEAKING OUT.  THE JENNINGS FIRE DEPARTMENT BUILT A DYKE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  LARCO ENVIRONMENTAL THEN NEUTRALIZED THE SUBSTANCE AT THE DIRECTION OF THE DEQ OUT OF BATON ROUGE, LA.  HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL WAS NOT REQUIRED.

AT 1820 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 8TH IN ALLENTOWN CLASSIFACATION YARD, CR EMPLOYEES NOTICED A SMALL CLOUD AT THE SAFETY VENT OF PLMX 200506.  AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR A. RITCHER FOUND THE 3516 MIDLAND SAFETY VALVE HAD APPARENTLY OPERATED RELEASING SOME PRODUCT.  RISK ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANED ALL RESIDUE PRODUCT FROM THE CAR ON SPETEMBER 9TH AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATION BECAUSE OF APPARENT LEAKAGE STAIN AND ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS 4-4 LITER GLASS BOTTLE WERE FOUND INSIDE.  TWO (2) OF THE BOTTLE WERE CRACKED WHICH RELEASED THE INNER CONTENTS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP AND ALONG WITH THE PACKAGE PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER INDICATING THE MATERIAL TO BE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELING ON THE OUTSIDE PACKAGE TO INDICATING THE INNER CONTENTS WERE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. A SHIPPER S CERTIFICATION WAS ALSO NOT PROVIDED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINSTRATION WAS CONTACTED WHERE SPECIAL AGENT RON BROWN WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE DRUM WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.
THIS CAR WAS OBSERVED WITH PRODUCT ON TOP OF CAR.  CHECK OF CAR REVEALED THE RUPTURE DISK HAD FAILED.  THE SIDE WAS REPLACED AND CAR ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.
PACKAGE WAS DROPPED AT UNLOAD.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE GLASS BOTTLES HAD BROKEN.

THE SECOND COMPARTMENT 1,050 GALLONS, WAS OVERLOADED AS THE LOADING SYSTEM WAS PRESET TO LOAD 3,400 GALLONS OF PRODUCT AND THE OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEM WAS BYPASSED. APPROXIMATELY 1,800 GALLONS SPILLED INTO THE LOADING RACK CONTAINMENT AREA BEFORE THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE LOADING RACK AND EXERCISED EMERGENCY SHUT DOWN OF THE LOADING PROCESS. THE 1,800 SPILL OF GASOLINE WAS CONTAINED IN THE LOADING RACK CONTAINMENT AREA AND WAS RECOVERED VIA TRENCH DRAINS LEADING TO AN OIL/WATER SEPARATOR.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SIDE BUNG CAP OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS WAS LOOSE RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF THIS MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE VAN TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA OF THE FACILITY. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE FACILITY IDENTIFIED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED. IN ADDITION, ALL CONTAINERS THAT ARE FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE OR DAMAGED ARE TO BE IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 761 MIDDLE STREET IN BRISTON, CT TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC.  LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP,THE DRIVER STOPPED AT A WEIGH STATION LOCATED AT I-80 WEST IN HUBBARD, OH.  DURING THIS STOP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP BUNG CAP OF TWO OF THE DRUMS AND POOLED ON THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE CREW ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH AN ABSORBANT PAD AND TIGHTENED THE LOOSE BUNG CAP.  ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM USED TO OVERPACK A SECOND CONTAINER FROM THIS SHIPMENT (SEE EXHIBIT 3) AND WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE FACILITY IDENTIFIED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING GAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

OF OUR SORT FACILITY 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON,OHIO. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND P/T HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICAN JIM GILLIAM RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. THE SECOND BOX CONTAINED 12-8 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES OF "GUMOUT SMALL ENGINE GAS TREATMENT". THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. WILMINGTON OHIO 45177. HE REPORTED THE ODOR AS "GLUE" WITH 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND P/T HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICAN ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED TO THE ODOR. UPON ARRIVAL, WE FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE, EMITTING AN ODOR OF GLUE. WE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 4-LKG METAL CONTAINERS OF "STANDO SOFT FEIN PLASTIC". THREE OF THESE METAL CONTAINERS SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE AROUND THE SEAL OF THE CLOSURES. APPROXIMATE AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE, 2 OUNCES THERE WAS ALSO SIGNS OF INNER CONTAINER COMPROMISE IN THE FORM OF DENTING. THE MANUFACTURES LABEL ON THE INNER CONTAINERS WERE MARKED WITH THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: PAINT UN 1263. ALSO INCLUDED IN THE BOX WERE 2-2KG  METAL CONTAINERS OF "TOP STOPPER". ON THE MANUFACTURES LABEL OF THESE CONTAINERS IS THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: PHOTOCHEMICALLY REACTIVE UN1263. THE FINAL ITEM IN THE BOX IS A SMALL UN/4G/YL/92 FIBREBOARD BOX WITH THE HAZARD LABEL FOR ORGANIC PEROXIDE PREPRINTED ON THE BOX. INSIDE THE BOX ARE 4-60G PLASTIC TUBES CONTAINING "STANDOX HARDNER PASTE" INDICATED ON ONE OF THE PLASTIC TUBES IS THE FOLLOWING: UN3108. WE RESEALED THE BOX, PLACED THE BOX INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS, THEN LOCKED THIS BOX INSIDE THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID CABINET IN THE HAZ MAT AREA FOR FAA INVESTIGATION. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ATTACHED TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE PACKAGING OF FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS AND ORGANIC PEROXIDES IN THE SAME PACKAGE IS FORBIDDEN BY 49 CFR DUE TO THE REACTIVITY OF THESE TYPE CHEMICALS.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Derailment; Rollover Accident
column168: TANK CAR INVOLVED IN DERAILMENT LEAVING CAR LYING ON ITS SIDE. AFTER A SHORT TIME, A SMALL LEAK DEVELOPED FROM THE VACUM RELIEF VALVE. PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF ABOUT TWO DROPS PER MINUTE. UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY T.M. ROBINSON RESPONDED AND WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE VALVE FROM LEAKING. ROBINSON APPLIED SORBANT PADS AROUND AND THIS SECURED THE DRIPPAGE UNTIL THE CAR COULD BE RIGHTED. DURING THE RERAILING OPERATION, DEBRIS ON THE GROUND CAUSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO OPEN AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BEGAN DRIPPING PAST THE OUTLET NOZZLE CAP. THE OPERATING HANDLE WAS NOW BENT SUCH THAT IT PREVENTED THE VALVE FROM CLOSING ALL OF THE WAY. ROBINSON TIGHTENED THE OUTLET NOZZLE CAP ABOUT ONE HALF TURN AND THIS STOPPED THE LEAKAGE. BECAUSE OF THE DAMAGE FROM THE DERAILMENT AND RERAILING OPERATION THE SHIPMENT WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSLOADED AND TO ANOTHER CAR. IN ADDITION TO CHEMTREC, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND TO BORDEN CHEMICALS, THE SHIPPER. ON SUNDAY, 9/11/94, ROBINSON, ALONG WITH MR. FARLEY KINCHEN, DISTRIBUTION SUPERVISOR FOR BORDEN AT GEISMAR, LA. AND UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, R.M. STINE, TRANSFERRRED THE SHIPMENT UTLX 642742 TO GATX 34344. THE CARS WERE PROPERLY SPOTTED AT 1430 HOURS AND PRODUCT WAS FLOWING AT ABOUT 1500 HOURS. PRODUCT TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AT ABOUT 1750 HOURS. THE CARS WERE SECURED AND RELEASED TO THE SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS AT LIVONIA AT 1845 HOURS. THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT INCIDENT. MR. KINCHEN REQUESTED THAT GATX 34344 MOVE ONTO DESTINATION UNDER THE ORIGINAL BILLING AND ROUTING FROM UTLX 642742. ON MONDAY, 9/12/94, UPRR CLAIMS REPRESENTATIVE MS. CARROL LINGO WAS CONTACTED AND PROVIDED INFORMATION FROM THE INCIDENT. MS. LINGO  UPDATED THE BILLING AND WILL PROVIDE FOLLOW UP FOR THE DISPOSITION OF THE DAMAGED CAR.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 1530 HRS. ON MONDAY THE 12TH OF SEPTEMBER MGR. C.T.S. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY M.T.O. SCOTT MURRAY AT POCATELLO ID. REGARDING TANK CAR GATX30768, REPORTED LEAKING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. IT WAS DETERMINED, UPON ARRIVAL THAT AN EMPLOYEE HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO THE LEAKING VAPOR, ON THE PRECEEDING SATURDAY, REPORTED AS INCIDENT 0994WT003. THE CAR WAS FINALLY LOCATED, AND SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION REVEALED THE LEAK WAS THE RESULT OF LOOSE PACKING IN THE LIQUID VALVE ON THE B END OF THE CAR. ALSO, VALVE SLIGHTLY OPEN, AND 2" PLUG WAS LOOSE. ALL REPAIRS COMPLETED AT 1904 HRS, CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 1100 HRS. ON THE 13TH DAY OF SEPTEMBER MGR. C.T.S. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY REGIONAL MGR. WHITELEY, REGARDING A LEAKING TANKCAR UTLX48004 AT YERMO CA. M.T.O. GARY HUTTNER AT YERMO REPORTS THE CAR LEAKS FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED,CAR IS SET OUT ON THE CLEANING TRACK NEAR THE DEPOT. MGR. RODABOUGH ARRIVED AT 1730 HRS. INSPECTION REVEALED THE MANWAY GASKET TO BE BROKEN, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO FLOW FROM THE TANKCAR WHEN MOVED. ALSO FOUR OF EIGHT SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE. THE OLD GASKET WAS REMOVED AND A TEMPORARY GORTEX GASKET WAS APPLIED. THE OLD GASKET WAS PLACED INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING TO BE INSPECTED BY THE SHIPPER. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED.

DATE/TIME UNION PACIFIC HINKLE YARD MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT FORCES HINKLE, OR. REPORTED TO REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITLELEY, PORTLAND, OR., THAT FRA INSPECTOR JOEL ROBERTSON FOUND FRANGIBLE DISC SAFETY VENT TANK CAR KCCX 2516, SULFURIC ACID, INBOUND TRAIN XOGHX 11, RECEIVING TRACK R-4, HINKLE, HAD FAILED. WHITELEY TRAVELED TO HINKLE NOTING BS&B 100 POUND DISC INSTALLED MIDLAND 2" BAFFLED SAFETY VENT MOUNTED INSIDE WORKING PLATFORM ON TANK CAR HAD RUPTURED. STAN ANDERSON, KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER, GARFIELD, UT., WAS FURNISHED DETAILS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: AT 1200HRS ON 9-12-94 WHILE CONDUCTING COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS, CTS MGR LERCH NOTED RESIDUE VAPOR EMITTING FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE LOCATED ON THE MANWAY COVER. REMOVAL AND INSPECTION OF 3 INCH VALVE REVEALED THAT THE O-RING WAS DEFECTIVE AND WAS THE CAUSE OF RELEASE. REPLACED VALVE WITH A 3 INCH PLUG WHICH STOPPED RELEASE AND SECURED CAR. MANWAY COVER SEALED WITH UPJ- 359877. NOTIFICATION; 1300 HRS, 9-112-94., MINNESOTA CORN PROCESSORS, GARY PAGEL, TRANSPORTATION COORDINATOR; 1310 HRS, CHEM-TREC, TRACY JACKSON, #31098; 1315 HRS, NEBRASKA D.E.Q., JOHN FOGERTY, 091394-JF-1315; UPRR M.D.I. JOHN STRUAB; 164HRS, UPRR E.M.G. STEVE MCNAUGHTON.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A.LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION, TRAIN DECY-14, EXTRA 9320 NORTH, NOTED LIQUID RUNNING DOWN LEFT SIDE OF TANK CAR. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT ONE INCH AIR CONNECTION VALVE WAS IN OPEN POSITION, WITH PIPE PLUG HANGING LOOSE FROM SAFETY CHAIN. SECURED VALVE AND PIPE PLUG, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. JIM COOPER, CHEMTREC FILE #31120 AND JOE BURNS, TOTAL PETROLEUM, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

S/A, BALLANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM THE STOCKTON TOWER THAT TANKCAR GATX-93400 WAS POSSIBLE LEAKING. S/A, BALLANCE ARRIVED AND PERFORMED A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE TANKCAR. NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF A LEAK WERE NOTED. A SMALL VAPOR LEAK COULD BE HEARD COMING FROM UNDER THE LID OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. THE HOUSING WAS OPENED APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES AFTER THE VAPOR LEAK WAS DETECTED. AT THIS TIME THE LEAK HAD STOPPED. THE FITTING AND VALVES WERE CHECKED FOR TIGHTNESS. THEY WERE ALSO SPRAYED WITH SNOOP. THE INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE AT 150 POUNDS. THE LID WAS CLOSED AND SECURED. THE LEAK WAS NOT FOUND. THE TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED AGAIN ON 091794 AT 1200 HRS. THERE WAS NO SIGN OF ANY LEAK AT THAT TIME. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL SERVICE.

WHILE CONDUCTING INSPECTION BLITZ, MANAGER S. COVI AND MANAGER P. STUDENT NOTED THAT THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS LOOSE. THE VAPOR VALVE WAS ALSO OPEN AND PLUG WAS LOOSE. BOTH VALVES WERE TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TURN AND THE PLUGS WERE TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELLY ON TURN. THE "A" END LIQUID LINE PLUG WAS REMOVED AND TEFLON WAS APPLIED TO ENSURE PROPER SECUREMENT. CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC (REPORT 31223) WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. CENTENNIAL WAS LISTED ON THE WAYBILL AS SHIPPER WITH CHEMTREC 800 NUMBER. CENTENNIAL WAS NOT LISTED WITH CHEMTREC BUT FURTHER RESEARCH DETERMINED THAT ENRON WAS THE COMPANY WHICH SUBMITTED THE BILL OF LADING AND "ENRON" IS LISTED WITH CHEMTREC.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE CONDUCTING INSPECTION BLITZ IN OGDEN, UT, IT WAS REPORTED THAT AMIX 300057 WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FORM THE MANWAY DURING MOVEMENT. MANAGER S. COVI AND OTHER UNION PACIFIC CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGERS RESPONDED. MANWAY GASKET WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE IN GOOD SHAPE. MANWAY GASKET WAS REVERSED AND BOLTS WERE SECURED. CAR WAS THEN MOVED FOR OBSERVATION. CAR STILL SPLASHED PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY. CLOSER INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY RETAINER ON THE MANWAY SWING BOLT AT THE MANWAY COVER HANDLE (IN COMPLIANCE WITH 179.201-6) WAS MIS-SHAPED WHICH PREVENTED PROPER SECUREMENT OF THE MANWAY. THE COLLAR WAS RESHAPED TO ALLOW PROPER SECUREMENT OF THE MANWAY AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WHILE CONDUCTING TANK CAR INSPECTION, FOUND TANK CAR GATX 67820 TO BE LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE BASE OF THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE, A PLUG TYPE ANGLE VALVE. THE VALVE HANDLE HAD BEEN RED TAGGED AS A "LEAKER". THE FOUR BASE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, WHICH GREATLY REDUCED THE VAPOR RELEASE, DID NOT COMPLETELY STOP THE LEAK.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WHILE CONDUCTING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, FOUND TANK CAR WRNX 30170 TO BE LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE GAUGING ROD. DEVELOPED THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. THE NUT WAS PROPERLY TIGHTENED AND SECURED, WHICH CURTAILED THE LEAF. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO HTE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WHILE CONDUCTING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, FOUND TANK CAR AMOX 33553 TO BE LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE GAUGING ROD. DEVELOPED THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. ALSO, THE 1/4" ANGLE VALVE ATOP THE GAUGING ROD WAS OPEN TWO FULL TURNS. BOTH WERE TIGHTENED AND SECURED, WHICH CURTAILED THE LEAK. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION, SOUTH 8 TRACK, NOTED LIQUID RUNNING DOWN BOTH SIDES, LIQUID COMING FROM PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT 2 INCH UNLOADING CONNECTION VALVE WAS IN OPEN POSITION, WITH PIPE PULG FINGER TIGHT.  IF 2-INCH UNLOADING CONNECTION VALVE HANDLE WAS IN CLOSED POSITION IT WOULD EXTEND BEYOND THE NOZZEL PLATE, DISALLOWING PROPER CLOSURE OF PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT SEAL UP-J-341356 WAS APPLIED TO PROTECTIVE HOUSEING.  VALVE AND PIPE PLUG WERE SECURED, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  HANDLE WAS REMOVED AND SELA UP-C-54673 WAS APPLIED TO PROTECTIVE.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT SALT LAKE CITY MGR. C.T.S. H.W. RODABROUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR CALX 3024, LOADED TANKCAR OF PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL.  NOTED 2" PLUG IN THE BALL VALVE LIQUID EDUCATION TUBE LOOSE LESS THAN FINGER TIGHT, 1" PLUG IN BALL VALVE VAPOR LINE LOOSE, LESS THAN FINGER TIGHT AN THE VACCUM RELEIF VALVE NOT FINCTIONING, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK.  CAR OWNER NOTIFIED, CRYSEN REFINING, MR. RANDY SPJUT, FLEET MGR. STATED THAT HE WOULD TAKE ACTION TO HAVE THE CAR REPAIRED AND SEE THAT THE CARS ARE SECURED FOR SHIPMENT.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: DURING TANK CAR AUDIT, OGDEN, UT, MANAGERS, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, P.J.STUDENT AND D.A. LOW, NOTED TANK CAR UTLX 88076, LEAKING FROM FROZEN ROD NUT ON MGM 60 SERIES GAUGING ROS ASSEMBLY.  ALL REPAIR ACTION, REDUCED VAPOR LEAK,  CAR WAS TAGGED AND SEL UP-C-54678 WAS APPLIED TO GAUGING ROD HOUSING.  DAVE MOSS, CHEVRON USE, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTION.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT TANK CAR IS BILLED TO UNION TANK CAR SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTION AT SALT LAKE CITY MGR C.T.S. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR CALX 3014, LOADED TANKCAR OF PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL.   NOTED SLIGHT LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, FOUND THE CAP TO BE LOOSE.  THIS WAS CORRECTED BY TIGHTENING THE CAP, LEAK STOPPED.  THIS IN VIOLATION OF DOE-6000-N-PART 173.31 SUB PART 18(B)(3). CAR OWNER CRYSEN REFINING NOTIFIED, MR RANDY SPJUT, FLEET MGR. STATED THAT HE WOULD TAKE ACTION TO SECURE THE CARS IN THE FUTURE.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT SALT LAKE CITY. MGR C.T.S. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANK CAR CLX 3039, LOADED TANKCAR OF PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL.  NOTED LEAK FROM THE AREA OF THE MANWAY COVER, FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT MANWAY GASKET MISSING, APPLIED A TEMPORARY GORTEX GASKET AND SECURED THE CAR.  THE CAR OWNER CRYSEN REFINING NOTIFIED,  MR. RANDY SPJUT, FLEET MGR, STATED THAT HE WOULD TAKE ACTION TO MAKE SURE THE SHIPMENTS, IN THE FUTURE ARE PROPERLY SECURED.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTION AT SALT LAKE CITY, MGT C.T.S. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR UTLX 88063 RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS.  NOTED SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK FROM THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GAUGING DEVICE, THIS WAS QUICKLY AND EASLY RESOLVED BY SIMPLY TIGHTENING THE NUT, A COUPLE OF TURNS. THIS IN VIOLATION OF BOE-6000-N PART 173.31.  SUB-PART 18(B)(3).  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED, RESULTING IN A CALL BACK BY AMOCO OIL, LARRY W. HOWARD, SUPERVISOR MAINTENANCE AND SERVICE. HE EXPRESSED APPRECIATION, FOR OUR SERVICES AND STATED THAT THEY WOULD TAKE ACTION TO ELIMINATE THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: INFORMATION RECEIVED FROM BRAD BISSELL, TERMINAL MANAGER, UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT, SEATTLE, AT APPROXIMATELY 0810 HOURS, 092294, ADVISING CONTAINER APLU 971486, PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, WITH A SECONARY POISON WAS NOTED LEAKING AT THE DEPARTURE GATE.  FURTHER, HE ADVISED IT UNLOADED FROM STACK CAR SP 513834 UNIT "C" AND PLACED IN THE "B ROW" OVERNIGHT. ALSO, HE ADVISED THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN ISOLATED PENDING MY ARRIVAL. *********************** THE INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BOTH ON THE GROUND IN THE "B ROW" AND IN THE WELL OF THE STACK CAR IN QUESTION.  FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INVOLVED NOTED IT TO BE LEAKING IN THE RIGHT FRONT NOSE PORTION.************* AN INTERIOR INSPECTION DEVELOPED IMPROPER AND INADEQUATE BLOCKING AND BRACING.  NOTED SEVERAL 15 GALLON PLASTIC PAILS LABELED UN2489 STACKED ON EACH OTHER WITHOUT ANY SEPARATION, ALLOWING THEM TO TIP CRASH INTO EACH OTHER CRUSHING AND FORCING THE INTERIOR PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE BUG.******************** DAVE FREITES, VICE PRESIDENT OPERATIONS AND JIM JOSLYN, CLAIMS MANAGER, WASHINGTON OREGON SHIPPERS, WERE CONTACTED AND THEY DIRECTLY CONTRACTED WITH FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOAD, TO OVERPACK THE LEAKING PAILS AND CLEAN THE GROUND IN "B ROW" AND THE STACK CAR SP 513834 UNIT "C" AND TRANSLOAD CONTAINER APLU 971846 CONTENTS INTO CONTAINER APLU 991511.  ************************ MEL FRANK, SITE SUPERVISOR, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, SEATTLE, ADVISED DURING THE CLEANUP OPERATION HIS FORCES NOTED 3 DIFFERENT ITEMS LEAKING. ITEM #1 UN1992 URI 6816 GRAY TAR, 1 5 GALLON METAL PAIL PUNCTURED AT THE BOTTOM LEAKING APPROXINATELY 1 QUART WHICH HAD COAGULATED STOPPING THE LEAK. ITEM #2 UN1992 URI 6821 BLACK TAR, 5 5 GALLON METAL PAILS WERE NOTED DENTED AND TO HAVE LEAKED AT THE LID COAGULATING TO THE SIDE OF THE PAILS AND ITEM #3 ULTRA FOAM CHEMICAL COMPOUND A, UN2489, 15 15 GALLON PAILS WERE NOTED TIP OVER CRUSHING INTO EACH OTHER CAUSING CONTENTS TO BE FORCED OUT THE BUNG. MR. FRANK STATED, HE DID NOT OBSERVE ANY SEPARATION MATERIAL BETWEEN THE STACKED 15 GALLON PAILS.  HOWEVER, DID NOTE AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO SEPARATE VARIOUS PRODUCTS BY PLACING SHEETS OF PLYWOOD UPRIGHT BETWEEN THEM IN THE REAR OF CONTAINER. **************** IT SHOULD ALSO BE NOTED THAT MR. FRANK STATED HE REQUESTED ASSISTANCE FROM THE CONSIGNEE GACO WESTERN INC. KENT, WA. AND THEIR REPRESENTATIVE CORINNE DUBBINS, RESPONDED.  SHE ADVISED MR. FRANK THAT THE ORIGIN SHIPPER (GACO WESTERN INC) OVER FILLED THE 15 GALLON PAILS IN QUESTIONS. ************************ CONTENTS OF CONTAINER APLU 971846 WAS TRANSLOADED, CONTAINER WAS CLEANED AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE TRANSLOADED INTO CONTAINER APLU 991511 WITH UP SEAL 184489 BEING APPLIED. CONTAINER APLU 991511 WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DELIVERY.

ITEM #2 UN1992 URI 6821 BLACK TAR, 5 5 GALLON METAL PAILS WERE NOTED DENTED AND TO HAVE LEAKED AT THE LID COAGULATING TO THE SIDE OF THE PAILS AND ITEM #3 ULTRA FOAM CHEMICAL COMPOUND A, UN2489, 15 15 GALLON PAILS WERE NOTED TIP OVER CRUSHING INTO EACH OTHER CAUSING CONTENTS TO BE FORCED OUT THE BUNG. MR. FRANK STATED, HE DID NOT OBSERVE ANY SEPARATION MATERIAL BETWEEN THE STACKED 15 GALLON PAILS.  HOWEVER, DID NOTE AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO SEPARATE VARIOUS PRODUCTS BY PLACING SHEETS OF PLYWOOD UPRIGHT BETWEEN THEM IN THE REAR OF CONTAINER. **************** IT SHOULD ALSO BE NOTED THAT MR. FRANK STATED HE REQUESTED ASSISTANCE FROM THE CONSIGNEE GACO WESTERN INC. KENT, WA. AND THEIR REPRESENTATIVE CORINNE DUBBINS, RESPONDED.  SHE ADVISED MR. FRANK THAT THE ORIGIN SHIPPER (GACO WESTERN INC) OVER FILLED THE 15 GALLON PAILS IN QUESTIONS. ************************ CONTENTS OF CONTAINER APLU 971846 WAS TRANSLOADED, CONTAINER WAS CLEANED AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE TRANSLOADED INTO CONTAINER APLU 991511 WITH UP SEAL 184489 BEING APPLIED. CONTAINER APLU 991511 WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DELIVERY.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: INFORMATION RECEIVED FROM BRAD BISSELLM TERMINAL MANAGER, UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGH, SEATTLE, AT 1330 HRS, 092294, ADVISING IMTANK BULKTAINER UPTU 530054 PLACARD NA3082 CLASS 90 WAS NOTED LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID FROM THE SPILL BOX DRAIN PIPES.  FURTHER, BRAD STATED THAT HIS FORCES HAD ISOLATED IT AND WERE WAITING MY ARRIVAL.  INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED THE IMTANK TO BE EQUIPPED WITH A COVERED SPILL BOX.  THE LID WAS OPENED REVEALING LIQUID RESIDUE RUNNING DOWN BELOW THE MANWAY COVER LID BETWEEN THE 6 O'CLOCK AND 9 O'CLOCK POSITION AS YOU FACE IT.  FURTHER, INVESTIGATION NOTED THE MANWAY COVER LID TO BE SEALED.  HOWEVER, 4 TO 6 COMPLETE TURNS WERE MADE ON EACH TO TIGHTENED THEM.  JOHN HAMMELMAN, UNOCAL PETROLEUM PRODUCTS AND CHEMICAL DIVISION, KENIA, AK. WAS CONTACTED. JOHN, ADVISED THEY HAVE BEEN TIGHTENING THE MANWAY COVER LID WING NUTS BY HAND ONLY.  HOWEVER WILL MAKE THEM WRENCH TIGHT FROM NOW ON.  IN ADDITION HE ADIVSED HIS FORCES WILL BE MONTORING THE NEXT SEVERAL SHIPMENTS TO INSURE THERE WILL BE NO FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE.

column168: PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATION BECAUSE OF APPARENT LEAKAGE, STAIN AND ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTES 2-1 QUART PLASTIC BOTTLE WERE FOUND INSIDE.  ONE OF THE BOTTLES HAD LEAKED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS FROM A LOOSE TOP. THE SPILLED MATERIAL CAUSE THE PAPER USED FOR CUSHIONING TO BURN.  A PACKING LIST INSIDE AN ENVELOPE INDICATED THE MATERIAL TO BE SULPHURIC ACID.  ONE EMPLOYEE HAD SOME OF THE MATERIAL SPILL ON THE FACE AND HANDS.  SHE WENT TO COMPANY CLINIC.  WASHED UP AND RETUNED BACK TO WORK.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELING ON THE OUTSIDE PACKAGE TO INDICATE THE INNER CONTENTS WERE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. A SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION WAS ALSO NOT PROVIDED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINSTRATION WAS CONTACTED WHERE MANAGER CHUCK BROCKMAN WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SHIPMENT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL ALONG WITH THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

PACKAGE WAS DROPPED AT LOADING.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD A RUPTURED SEAM THAT ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED.   PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: PACKAGE WAS DROPPED AT UNLOAD.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD LOOSE CAP.  THE CAP WAS SECURED.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED.  PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

XTO DRIVER B. MCCANCE AND S. KEESEY WERE UNLOADING TRAILER 415-3395 AT THE XTO DOCK ON 7/26/94.  NOTICED A LIQUID ON THE FLOOR AND AFTER MOVING A SKID OF MATERIAL FOUND 1 55 GALLON DRUM OF TRICHLORETHANE WITH A SMALL HOLE IN IT, FROM WHICH A SMALL AMOUNT OF LQUID WAS LEAKING.  THEY TURNED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO STOP THE MATERIAL FROM RUNNING OUT AND PUT ABSORBANT MATERIAL ON THE SPILL.  NOTIFIED FOS ON DUTY, MATT YEAGER, WHO HAD THEM LEAVE THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT ON THE TRAILER AND PULL IT AWAY FROM THE DOCK UNTIL IT COULD BE DETERMINED THE DISPOSAL, AND REST OF THE SHIPMENT WAS SENT ON FOR DELIVER ON 9/27/94.  LEAKING DRUM WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER ON 7/27/94 FOR TRANSFER AND HANDLING.

A DRIVER FOUND HIS TRAILER LEAKING AT A TIRE CHECK.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  A CERTIFIED RESPONDED TEAM WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND A HEAVY SKID WAS DISCOVERED LOADED ON TOP OF TWO METAL DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WERE PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW D.O.T. APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH APPROPRIATE LABELS AND MARKINGS.  THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP AND SPILLAGE WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

AT 1810 HOURS ON SEPTEMBER 20TH, THE CREWOF YANF 22 DISCOVERED GATX 20386 LEAKING FROM THE "TOP DONE" WHEN BRAKEMAN A.J. MORRCALE HAS PRODUCT SPRAY IN HIS FACE.  THIS OCCURED AS THE CREW AS PLACING THE CART TO BE WEIGHTED IN NIAGARA YARD.  A TEAM FROM OLIN REPLACED THE 135# SAFETY DISC THAT HAD RUPTURED.

DURING CTS TANK CAR AUDIT, ODGEN YARDS, MANAGERS, DEAN COOPER AND DON LOW, NOTED VAPORS COMING FROM 80CF VACCUM RELIEF VALVE, LOCATED IN MANWAY COVER.  VACCUM RELIEF VALVE WAS REMOVED AND PLUGGED, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. MILLIE GRAY, KERN OIL REFINING, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTION.

S/A BALLANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM CARMAN AGGUIE ACOSTA THAT TANKCAR SNHX 3122 WAS FOUND ON TRACK 21 LEAKING.  S/A, BALLANCE ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE TANKCAR.  THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE WAS FOUND TO HAVE A SMALL VAPOR LEAK FROM THE TWO INCH PLUG.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE LIQUID VALVE WAS BAD. PIPE TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE TWO INCH PLUG AND THEN SECURED WITH A WRENCH. THIS STOPPED THE RELEASE OF VAPOR.  MELVIN CRAWFORD OF CALIFORNIA AMMONIA WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.  IT WAS AGREED TO HAVE THE TANKCAR BAD ORDERED FOR RETURN TO CALIFORNIA AMMONIA.

S/A BALLANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM CARMEN TONY GREY THAT TANKCAR GATX 74190 ON TRACK 21 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  S/A, BALLANCE INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND FOUND A SMALL VAPOR RELEASE COMING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE PRESSURE OF THE CAR WAS TAKEN AND FOUND TO BE 150 POUNDS.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE IS SET FOR 255 POUNDS.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE VALVE WAS BAD.  MELVIN CRAWFORD WITH CALIFORNIA AMMONIA WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.  IT WAS AGREED THE TANKCAR WOULD BE PLACED INTO BAD ORDER STATUS FOR RETURN TO CALIFORNIA AMMONIA.

column62: Abrasion; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: 0400 SATURDAY, SEPTEMBER 24TH, 1994, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY STU WHITED WAS NOTIFIED BY SR. SPECIAL AGENT LOTMAN THAT TRAILER BMDZ 633315 ETHYL BUTYRATE ON CAR SOO 54847 IN TRACK 111 AT DUPO YARD HAD A STRONG ODOR AROUND THE AREA OF THE TRAILER, HOWEVER THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF A LEAK.  WHITED ARRIVED DUPO AT 0500 HOURS, SAME DATE, AND MADE INTERIOR INSPECTION OF TRAILER IN TRACK 111; AND AT WHICH TIME NOTED TRAILER LOADED WITH 55 GALLON DRUMS HAD NO BLOCKING OR BRACING AND IN THE FRONT OR THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER ELEVEN DRUMS WERE HANDED TOGETHER ON WOOD PALLETS STACKED ON TOP OF THE OTHER DRUMS WITH NOTHING TO SECURE DRUMS FROM MOVING AROUND IN TRAILER.  TRAILER WAS NOT PLACARDED, HOWEVER ALL DRUMS HAD FLAMMABLE UN1180 TABLES ATTACHED TO EACH DRUM.  AFTER INSPECTION OF TRAILER BMDZ 63315 REQUESTED YARDMASTER MOVE CAR TO THE DUPO INTERMODAL RAMP WHERE TRAILER WAS DERAMPED AND ISOLATED IN THE TRAILER REPAIR YARD WHERE PLACARDS WERE APPLIED TO TRAILER.  WHITED CONTACTED SHIPPER HUB CITY TERMINALS, LAREDO, TX., TELEPHONE 210-656-5520 AND SPOKE WITH SHIPPER REP. JOE GREGORY ADVISING THAT TRAILER BNDZ 633315 HAD ARRIVED DUPO WITH NO PLACARDS AND LOAD NOT BLOCKED OR BRACED; AND THAT ONE OR MORE THE DRUMS CONTAINING ETHYL BUTYRATE WERE LEAKING.  MR. GREGORY WAS FURTHER ADVISED THAT LOAD WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED AND ALL DRUMS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WOULD HAVE TO BE OVERPACKED AND LOAD BLOCKED AND BRACED AT HIS COMPANY'S EXPENSE.  GREGORY ADVISED WHITED THAT MINIE SERVICES OF ST LOUIS WOULD TRANSFER LOAD.  ON WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 19TH, 1994, MR. BILL FREESE OF MINIE SERVICES, ARRIVED AT DUPO TO TRANSFER TRAILER.  TRANSFER STARTED AT 1000 HOURS AND COMPLETED AT 1400 HOURS.  TWO DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED FOR LEAKS AND THIRD DRUM WAS OVER PACKED DUE TO HEAVY DAMAGED FROM SHIFTING OF LOAD.  MR. FREESE ADVISED HUB CITY TERMINALS WOULD BE CHARGED $900.00 FOR THE TRANSFER, BLOCKING AND BRACING OF TRAILER BMDZ 633315 AND $300.00 FOR THE OVERPACK DRUMS.  TOTAL OF $1200.00.  CONTENTS OF TRAILER BMDZ 633315 TRANSFERRED INTO TRAILER VTRZ 238464, AND SEAL UPZ-260281 APPLIED.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY GARY HUNTER, MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT A TANK CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS LEFT IN THE EAST END OF YARD TRACK #10 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE (8) BOLT RETAINER WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 56 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

AT 1300 HRS.  ON TUESDAY THE 27TH THE DAY OF SEPTEMBER, MGR. H. W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. CECIL HARRIS CARFOREMAN AT ELKO NV. REGARDING CAR GAPX9081.  THE CAR WAS REPORTED LEAKING AND HAD BEEN SET OUT ON TRACK #25 FOR REPAIR.  ON INSPECTION, CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WITH CRYSTALIZED PRODUCT ON THE MANWAY AND DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED A BROKEN RUPTURE DISC.  BROKEN DISC WAS REPLACED WITH A BS&B 100 LB.  DISC AND THE CAR WAS WASHED WITH WATER.  REPAIR COMPLETED 1830 HRS AND CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  REPORT TO CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER GEORGIA GULF CORP, ALLICE KAHL.

KELLY THAT THERE WAS A STRONG ODER COMING FROM THE ABOVE CAR.  KELLY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE O RING WAS MISSING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE VACCUM RELIEF VALVE. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 HOURS, 09/28/94, CARMAN WORKING 305 OUTBOUND RAIL IN THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK TERMINAL REPORTED A LARGE VAPOR CLOUD FORMING OVER TANKCAR EDCX 6008.  TRAIN OPERATIONS WERE IMMEDIATELY SUSPENDED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2000 HRS, SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, R.L. CARMAN AND MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, DOYLE RANKIN INSPECTED THE ONE INCH AIR LINE TO CHECK THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND DISCOVERED THE ONE INCH LINE CONTAINED LIQUID, WHICH INDICATES THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED.  AT 2049 HOURS, EDCX WAS PLACED AT THE FREIGHT HOUSE AND YARD OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  AT 2100 HOURS, GERALD MARTIN OF EL DORADO CHEMICAL WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION.  MARTIN ADVISED HE WOULD RESPOND WITH A TANK TRUCK TO OFF LOAD SOME OF THE PRODUCT CTS SPECIALIST, MIKE KELLY WAS ALSO CONTACTED AND HE RESPONDED FROM FT. SMITH, ARKANSAS.  GERALD MARTIN, EL DORADO CHEMICAL, ARRIVED AT 0200 HOURS, 09/29.  THE TRANSFER OF 1426 GALLONS OF NITRIC ACID WAS COMPLETED AT 0315 HOURS.  TRAIN OPERATIONS WERE AGAIN HALTED AFTER THE TRANSFER WHEN THE WASHING OF THE DOME OF THE CAR CAUSED A LARGE VAPOR CLOUD.  AFTER WASHING, THE CAR WAS INSPECTED WITH NO OTHER DEFECTS FOUND. A SECURITY GUARD AT A SALVAGE COMPANY LOCATED 1/8TH MILE FROM THE FREIGHT HOUSE REPORTED BEING OVERCOME BY VAPORS.  HE REFUSED THE FREIGHT HOUSE REPORTED BEING OVERCOME BY VAPORS.  HE REFUSED MEDICAL TREATMENT. YARD OPERATIONS RESUMED AT 0430 HRS & CAR EDCX 6008 RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED.

AT 1130 HRS. ON WEDNESDAY THE 28TH OF SEPTEMBER, MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. SCOTT THOMAS CORRIDOR MGR.  ON THE WESTERN DIVISION, REPORTS TRAIN SCEK 29 IS AT WENDOVER WILL BE SETTING OUT LEAKING TANKCAR OF ARGON GAS.  FURTHER REPORTS THE WENDOVER FIRE DEPT. IS ON SCENE. INSPECTION ON ARRIVAL AT 1340 HRS.  REVEALED THE LIQUID VALVES ON TOP OF THE CAR HAD VIBRATED OPEN, WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO LEAK, WHICH IN TURN ICED THE PIPES WHICH FEED INTO THE CONTROL PANNELS ON THE SIDES OF THE CAR.  THE OPERATING WHEETLS WERE WIRED IN SUCH A FASHION AS TO ALLOW BOTH VALVES TO OPEN WITH THE WIRE IN TACT.  THE VALVES WERE CLOSED AND THE OPERATING WHEELS RE-WIRED IN A FASHION AS TO PREVENT EITHER VALVE FROM OPENING.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED, MR. BILL GASSON REPORT #31396, SHIPPER ALSO NOTIFIED REGARDING THE METHOD OF SECURING THE OPERATING WHEELS, STATED THEY WOULD LOOK INTO IT.

MANGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW WAS CONTACTED BY CHEYENNE YARD MASTER, ADVISING A STRONG ODOR WAS COMING FROM TANK CARS, SOUTH 11 TRACK, COASTAL CHEM CUT.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT VAPOR LEAK WAS COMING FROM BASE OF THE TWO- INCH UNLOADING CONNECTION VALVE.  MANAGER, D.A. LOW, APPLIED GOR-TEX TO BHE BASE OF THE VALVE AND SECURED THE FOUR NUTS, WHICH SECURED THE NOZZLE PLATE COVER, AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  SIDNEY WHITE, COASTAL CHEM AND RON ALBER, AAR/BOE INSPECTOR, WERE NOTIFIED OF THE EXCEPTION.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER HAD INTACT SEAL UP-V-165034 APPLIED.

AT 0600 HRS.  ON WEDNESDAY THE 29TH OF SEPTEMBER MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. JOHN LYON M.T.O. AT OGDEN, HE REPORTS SWITCH OUT A STRING OF FOUR CARS, THEY ARE NOT SURE WHICH CAR OR CARS IN RESPONSIBLE. INSPECTION BY MGR. RODABOUGH REVEALED CAR ADMX 30206 WAS LEAKING FROMT HE BASE OF THE 3" BALL VALVE ASSEMBLY.  THIS IS A NEW CAR BUILT 7/94, OBVIOUSLY THE VALVE ASSEMBLY HAD NOT BEEN SECURED.  THE 3' PLUG WAS LESS THEN FINGER TIGHT AND THE 1' AIR PLUG WAS LOOSE.  ALL THIS IN VIOLATEION OF BOE-600-N PART 173.31 SUB-PART 18(B) (3).  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED, MR JIM COOPER, MADE REPORT AND WILL CALL SHIPPER.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION, WITHOUT FURTHER PROBLEM.

AT 1445 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 26, 1994, THE CONDUCTOR ON TRAIN YP014 REPORTED PRODUCT ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 94402.  GENERAL CAR FOREMAN INSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE VAPOR LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE.  THE CAR WAS SUSEQUENTLY ISOLATED.  INITIAL COMMUNICATIONS BETWEEN CONRAIL AND THE SHIPPER (LAROCHE) FAILED TO OBTAIN NECESSARY PERSONNEL FROM SHIPPER TO RESPOND TO LEAK.  ADDITIONAL CONTACT TO GATX CORP.  ALSO FAILED TO FIND PERSONNEL CAPABLE OF WORKING ON CAR. GAUGING DEVICE VALVE WAS SUBSEQUENTLY TIGHTENED BY NJDEP AND NEWARD FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HOURS.  CAR WAS REINSPECTED BY AAR/BOE ALLEN RICHTER AT 2030 HOURS.  MR. RICHTER INDICATED THAT THE CAR HAD A DUPONT REPAUNO PLANT SEAL AND THE CAR MAY HAVE BEEN RECEIVED BY LAROCHE FROM DUPONT AND PULLED FROM THE LAROCHE LODI PLANT WITH SEAL INTACT.
PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS PUNCTURED BY OTHER MATERIALS WITHIN THE PACKAGE.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: (A) PACKAGE WAS UNMARKED HAZARD 1 OF 3 AEROSOL CANS OF SPRAY ENAMEL PAINT RELEASED APPROX. 6 OZ. OF PAINT DUE TO LOOSE TOP.  (B) BROUGHT LEAKING PACKAGE TO DMP AREA.  WORE PROPER PPE AS OUTLINED IN FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  USED SOLUSORB TO ABSORB SPILLED LIQUID. DAMAGED PORTION ENTERED INTO DMP PROGRAM.  UNDAMAGED PORTION RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

KEVIN BUREK RESPONDED TO THE DAMAGED PACKAGE IN THE PRIMARY UNLOAD AND USING PERSONAL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT AND DECISION TREE, IDENTIFIED THE WET PACKAGE AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID. column58: Auxiliary Valve; Cylinder Neck or Shoulder; Cylinder Sidewall - Other; Piping or Fittings
column168: ARRIVED SEATTLE WITH STRONG ODOR OF ROTTEN EGGS. THE CYLINDER WAS PLACED IN A LINE TRAILER & THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED IN THE TERMINAL YARD. THE SHIPPER & CHEMTREC WERE CALLED & THE SHIPPER RESPONDED AND SAID THEY WOULD FLY THEIR REP TO SEATTLE FROM NEWARK, CA. THE SHIPPER REP INSPECTED THE CYLINDER, TIGHTENED THE HEAD 1/4 TURN, AND DISCOVERED THERE WAS NO VALVE CAP. THE REP INSPECTED THE OTHER 5 SHIPMENTS THAT WERE ON THE TRAILER AND AFTER CONSULTED WITH HIS MANAGER (BRAD CASEY) AND SCOTT'S ENGINEER, THEY DECLARED THE 5 SHIPMENTS WERE NOT CONTAMINATED.ON 10-4-94 THE SHIPPER REP (ADAM LAMB) INSTALLED A VALVE CAP AND PROCLAIMED THE CYLINDER OK FOR SHIPMENT. THE CYLINDER WAS SENT TO SCOTT (NEWARK, CA) ON PRO 540-503972.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE OCCURED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AS THERE WAS A VERY PUNGENT ODOR ASSOCIATED WITH THE SPILL.  THE HANDLERS NEGOIATING THE SPILL FOUND THE SUBSTANCE WAS HOT TO THE TOUCH AND HAD STARTED TO OXIDIZE/BURN THE PAPER IN THE PACKAGE BEING UTILIZED AS PACKING MATERIAL.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THE INFORMATION GIVEN CONFIRMED THAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  THERE WAS ALSO DOCUMENTATION ON THE INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE THAT WAS DAMAGED OUT WAS STILL ABLE TO BE SALVAGED THAT ALSO CONFIRMED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS  CORROSIVE.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS LABELS, MARKINGS, NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  TWO OF THE THREE EMPLOYEES DEALING WITH THE CLEANUP OF THE MATERIAL, SHERITA DOUGLAS, CONNIE LAMBERT, & KIN JONES WERE EXPOSED TO THE SUBSTANCE.  ALL THREE WENT TO THE CLINIC AND WERE RELEASED THE PACKAGE IS BEING HELD PENDING NOTIFICATIONS OF THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKING WAS NOTICED.  THIS WAS AN OVERPACK SITUATION AND THE INNER MOST CONTAINERS IN THE OVERPACK APPARENTLY WERE NOT ORIENTATED CORRECTLY IN THE PACKAGE CONTRARY TO THE OUTERMOST PACKAGE INDICATORS.  THE BOTTLE TOWARDS THE BOTTOM OF THE INNER PACKAGING LEAKED AS A RESULT OF OTHER INNER CONTAINERS CRUSHING THE CONTAINER.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE.  THE CONTAINER IS BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER IN PROCESS OF FILLING MANIFOLD, U.S.T. WHEN FLOW STOPPED. CONSIGNEE ATTEMPTED TO DETERMINE PROBLEM AND REMOVED A TANK FILL CAP WHICH RESULTED IN A SPILL.  THE TANK EQUALIZING LINE IS APPARENTLY BLOCKED.

THE BOX WAS DROPPED DURING THE TRANSLOAD.  UPON HITTING THE GROUND, ONE OF THE GLASS INNER CONTAINERS BROKE OPEN AND SPILLED ITS CONTENTS.  THE ABSORBANT MATERIAL PROVIDED WAS NEWSPAPER.  THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: I RESPONDED TO A MAJOR ACCIDENT WHICH OCCURRED IN BENTON, AR AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 AM ON SEPTEMBER 22, 1994.  THE ACCIDENT INVOLVED TWO TRACTOR TRAILER UNITS.  ONE UNIT WAS BEING OPERATED BY A CALVIN RUTLEDGE EMPLOYED BY BUILDERS TRANSPORT BASED OUT OF MEMPHIS, TN.  MR. RUTLEGE WAS HAULING STEEL BEAMS ON A FLAT BED TRAILER.  THE OTHER TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS BEING OPERATED BY DON BLALOCK (DRIVER) AND DALE MULKEY (IN SLEEPER) BOTH EMPLOYED BY LEASED DRIVER'S INC. CONTRACTED BY THE ACE PRODUCT BASED OUT OF MAUMELLE, AR.  MR. RUTLEDGE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON INTERSTATE 30 IN BENTON, AR WHEN HE CROSSED THE MEDIAN NEAR MILE MARKER 115.  UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT TIPPED OVER SLIDING ON THE PAVEMENT (DRIVER'S SIDE) INTO THE SOUTHBOUND LANES IOF INTERSTATE 30. WHEN MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT HIT A CURB LOCATED ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE INTERSTATE THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER (FLAT BED) TO BE UPRIGHTED.  THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB AND UPRIGHTING THE UNIT CAUSED A LOAD OF STEEL BEAMS APPROXIMATELY 20' - 30' IN LENGTH TO EJECT FROM THE FLAT BED.  DAN BLALOCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 30 AND ATTEMPTED TO AVOID HITTING THE DEBRIS IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANES BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL AS THE EVENTS DESCRIBED ABOVE TRANSPIRED VERY QUICKLY.  THE FORCE OF IMPACT OR THE DEBRIS ON THE ROAD CAUSED THE FUEL TANK OF THE RYDER TRACTOR TO RUPTURE WHEREBY A FIRE ENSUED.  THE FIRE EVENTUALLY IGNITED FLAMMABLES AND OTHER COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER CAUSING A MASSIVE FIRE.  AMMUNITION AND AEROSOL SPRAY PAINT WAS ALSO IN THE TRAILER CAUSING THESE PRODUCTS TO EXPLODE MAKING IT DIFFICULT FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNITS TO COMBAT AND CONTROL THE SCENE.  DAN BLALOCK WAS KILLED IN THE ACCIDENT.  DALE MULKEY RECEIVED A BROKEN SHOULDER AND MASSIVE BRUISES TO HIS ENTIRE BODY WITH HIGH CONCENTRATIONS TO THE LEFT SIDE, HE WAS ADMITTED TO THE SALINE COUNTY MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN BENTON, AR.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE WAS TREATED FOR MINOR ABRASIONS AT THE SAME HOSPITAL AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY, EARLY MORNING.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE RECEIVED A TRAFFIC CITATION FOR CROSSING THE MEDIAN.  THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE BELIEVE THAT MR. RUTLEDGE WAS EITHER SPEEDING OR SLEEPING AT THE WHEEL UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, THE REASONING OF WHICH IS EXPLAINED IN THE BODY OF THE REPORT. ACE CONTACTED SPILLTECH SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE DEBRIS LEFT ON THE ROAD WHICH WAS REDUCED TO A PILE OF BURNT HAZARDOUS WASTE DUE TO THE CHEMICALS WHICH BURNED AND THE AMMUNITIOIN STILL IN THE PILE.  THE ROAD WAS NOT CLEARED TO THROUGH TRAFFIC UNTIL 2:15 PM THE SAME DAY.  ALL PRODUCT WHICH BELONGED TO ACE IN THE TRAILER WAS A TOTAL LOSS, THE EXACT DOLLAR FIGURE WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE ONCE RECEIVED.  THE RYDER TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED.  PHOTOGRAPHS AND VIDEO WERE TAKEN OF THE SCENE AND WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A MAJOR ACCIDENT WHICH OCCURRED IN BENTON, AR AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 AM ON SEPTEMBER 22, 1994.  THE ACCIDENT INVOLVED TWO TRACTOR TRAILER UNITS.  ONE UNIT WAS BEING OPERATED BY A CALVIN RUTLEDGE EMPLOYED BY BUILDERS TRANSPORT BASED OUT OF MEMPHIS, TN.  MR. RUTLEGE WAS HAULING STEEL BEAMS ON A FLAT BED TRAILER.  THE OTHER TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS BEING OPERATED BY DON BLALOCK (DRIVER) AND DALE MULKEY (IN SLEEPER) BOTH EMPLOYED BY LEASED DRIVER'S INC. CONTRACTED BY THE ACE PRODUCT BASED OUT OF MAUMELLE, AR.  MR. RUTLEDGE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON INTERSTATE 30 IN BENTON, AR WHEN HE CROSSED THE MEDIAN NEAR MILE MARKER 115.  UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT TIPPED OVER SLIDING ON THE PAVEMENT (DRIVER'S SIDE) INTO THE SOUTHBOUND LANES IOF INTERSTATE 30. WHEN MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT HIT A CURB LOCATED ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE INTERSTATE THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER (FLAT BED) TO BE UPRIGHTED.  THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB AND UPRIGHTING THE UNIT CAUSED A LOAD OF STEEL BEAMS APPROXIMATELY 20' - 30' IN LENGTH TO EJECT FROM THE FLAT BED.  DAN BLALOCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 30 AND ATTEMPTED TO AVOID HITTING THE DEBRIS IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANES BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL AS THE EVENTS DESCRIBED ABOVE TRANSPIRED VERY QUICKLY.  THE FORCE OF IMPACT OR THE DEBRIS ON THE ROAD CAUSED THE FUEL TANK OF THE RYDER TRACTOR TO RUPTURE WHEREBY A FIRE ENSUED.  THE FIRE EVENTUALLY IGNITED FLAMMABLES AND OTHER COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER CAUSING A MASSIVE FIRE.  AMMUNITION AND AEROSOL SPRAY PAINT WAS ALSO IN THE TRAILER CAUSING THESE PRODUCTS TO EXPLODE MAKING IT DIFFICULT FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNITS TO COMBAT AND CONTROL THE SCENE.  DAN BLALOCK WAS KILLED IN THE ACCIDENT.  DALE MULKEY RECEIVED A BROKEN SHOULDER AND MASSIVE BRUISES TO HIS ENTIRE BODY WITH HIGH CONCENTRATIONS TO THE LEFT SIDE, HE WAS ADMITTED TO THE SALINE COUNTY MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN BENTON, AR.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE WAS TREATED FOR MINOR ABRASIONS AT THE SAME HOSPITAL AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY, EARLY MORNING.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE RECEIVED A TRAFFIC CITATION FOR CROSSING THE MEDIAN.  THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE BELIEVE THAT MR. RUTLEDGE WAS EITHER SPEEDING OR SLEEPING AT THE WHEEL UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, THE REASONING OF WHICH IS EXPLAINED IN THE BODY OF THE REPORT. ACE CONTACTED SPILLTECH SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE DEBRIS LEFT ON THE ROAD WHICH WAS REDUCED TO A PILE OF BURNT HAZARDOUS WASTE DUE TO THE CHEMICALS WHICH BURNED AND THE AMMUNITIOIN STILL IN THE PILE.  THE ROAD WAS NOT CLEARED TO THROUGH TRAFFIC UNTIL 2:15 PM THE SAME DAY.  ALL PRODUCT WHICH BELONGED TO ACE IN THE TRAILER WAS A TOTAL LOSS, THE EXACT DOLLAR FIGURE WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE ONCE RECEIVED.  THE RYDER TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED.  PHOTOGRAPHS AND VIDEO WERE TAKEN OF THE SCENE AND WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A MAJOR ACCIDENT WHICH OCCURRED IN BENTON, AR AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 AM ON SEPTEMBER 22, 1994.  THE ACCIDENT INVOLVED TWO TRACTOR TRAILER UNITS.  ONE UNIT WAS BEING OPERATED BY A CALVIN RUTLEDGE EMPLOYED BY BUILDERS TRANSPORT BASED OUT OF MEMPHIS, TN.  MR. RUTLEGE WAS HAULING STEEL BEAMS ON A FLAT BED TRAILER.  THE OTHER TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS BEING OPERATED BY DON BLALOCK (DRIVER) AND DALE MULKEY (IN SLEEPER) BOTH EMPLOYED BY LEASED DRIVER'S INC. CONTRACTED BY THE ACE PRODUCT BASED OUT OF MAUMELLE, AR.  MR. RUTLEDGE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON INTERSTATE 30 IN BENTON, AR WHEN HE CROSSED THE MEDIAN NEAR MILE MARKER 115.  UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT TIPPED OVER SLIDING ON THE PAVEMENT (DRIVER'S SIDE) INTO THE SOUTHBOUND LANES IOF INTERSTATE 30. WHEN MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT HIT A CURB LOCATED ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE INTERSTATE THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER (FLAT BED) TO BE UPRIGHTED.  THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB AND UPRIGHTING THE UNIT CAUSED A LOAD OF STEEL BEAMS APPROXIMATELY 20' - 30' IN LENGTH TO EJECT FROM THE FLAT BED.  DAN BLALOCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 30 AND ATTEMPTED TO AVOID HITTING THE DEBRIS IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANES BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL AS THE EVENTS DESCRIBED ABOVE TRANSPIRED VERY QUICKLY.  THE FORCE OF IMPACT OR THE DEBRIS ON THE ROAD CAUSED THE FUEL TANK OF THE RYDER TRACTOR TO RUPTURE WHEREBY A FIRE ENSUED.  THE FIRE EVENTUALLY IGNITED FLAMMABLES AND OTHER COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER CAUSING A MASSIVE FIRE.  AMMUNITION AND AEROSOL SPRAY PAINT WAS ALSO IN THE TRAILER CAUSING THESE PRODUCTS TO EXPLODE MAKING IT DIFFICULT FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNITS TO COMBAT AND CONTROL THE SCENE.  DAN BLALOCK WAS KILLED IN THE ACCIDENT.  DALE MULKEY RECEIVED A BROKEN SHOULDER AND MASSIVE BRUISES TO HIS ENTIRE BODY WITH HIGH CONCENTRATIONS TO THE LEFT SIDE, HE WAS ADMITTED TO THE SALINE COUNTY MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN BENTON, AR.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE WAS TREATED FOR MINOR ABRASIONS AT THE SAME HOSPITAL AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY, EARLY MORNING.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE RECEIVED A TRAFFIC CITATION FOR CROSSING THE MEDIAN.  THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE BELIEVE THAT MR. RUTLEDGE WAS EITHER SPEEDING OR SLEEPING AT THE WHEEL UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, THE REASONING OF WHICH IS EXPLAINED IN THE BODY OF THE REPORT. ACE CONTACTED SPILLTECH SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE DEBRIS LEFT ON THE ROAD WHICH WAS REDUCED TO A PILE OF BURNT HAZARDOUS WASTE DUE TO THE CHEMICALS WHICH BURNED AND THE AMMUNITIOIN STILL IN THE PILE.  THE ROAD WAS NOT CLEARED TO THROUGH TRAFFIC UNTIL 2:15 PM THE SAME DAY.  ALL PRODUCT WHICH BELONGED TO ACE IN THE TRAILER WAS A TOTAL LOSS, THE EXACT DOLLAR FIGURE WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE ONCE RECEIVED.  THE RYDER TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED.  PHOTOGRAPHS AND VIDEO WERE TAKEN OF THE SCENE AND WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE.

THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB AND UPRIGHTING THE UNIT CAUSED A LOAD OF STEEL BEAMS APPROXIMATELY 20' - 30' IN LENGTH TO EJECT FROM THE FLAT BED.  DAN BLALOCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 30 AND ATTEMPTED TO AVOID HITTING THE DEBRIS IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANES BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL AS THE EVENTS DESCRIBED ABOVE TRANSPIRED VERY QUICKLY.  THE FORCE OF IMPACT OR THE DEBRIS ON THE ROAD CAUSED THE FUEL TANK OF THE RYDER TRACTOR TO RUPTURE WHEREBY A FIRE ENSUED.  THE FIRE EVENTUALLY IGNITED FLAMMABLES AND OTHER COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER CAUSING A MASSIVE FIRE.  AMMUNITION AND AEROSOL SPRAY PAINT WAS ALSO IN THE TRAILER CAUSING THESE PRODUCTS TO EXPLODE MAKING IT DIFFICULT FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNITS TO COMBAT AND CONTROL THE SCENE.  DAN BLALOCK WAS KILLED IN THE ACCIDENT.  DALE MULKEY RECEIVED A BROKEN SHOULDER AND MASSIVE BRUISES TO HIS ENTIRE BODY WITH HIGH CONCENTRATIONS TO THE LEFT SIDE, HE WAS ADMITTED TO THE SALINE COUNTY MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN BENTON, AR.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE WAS TREATED FOR MINOR ABRASIONS AT THE SAME HOSPITAL AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY, EARLY MORNING.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE RECEIVED A TRAFFIC CITATION FOR CROSSING THE MEDIAN.  THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE BELIEVE THAT MR. RUTLEDGE WAS EITHER SPEEDING OR SLEEPING AT THE WHEEL UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, THE REASONING OF WHICH IS EXPLAINED IN THE BODY OF THE REPORT. ACE CONTACTED SPILLTECH SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE DEBRIS LEFT ON THE ROAD WHICH WAS REDUCED TO A PILE OF BURNT HAZARDOUS WASTE DUE TO THE CHEMICALS WHICH BURNED AND THE AMMUNITIOIN STILL IN THE PILE.  THE ROAD WAS NOT CLEARED TO THROUGH TRAFFIC UNTIL 2:15 PM THE SAME DAY.  ALL PRODUCT WHICH BELONGED TO ACE IN THE TRAILER WAS A TOTAL LOSS, THE EXACT DOLLAR FIGURE WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE ONCE RECEIVED.  THE RYDER TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED.  PHOTOGRAPHS AND VIDEO WERE TAKEN OF THE SCENE AND WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE.

DALE MULKEY RECEIVED A BROKEN SHOULDER AND MASSIVE BRUISES TO HIS ENTIRE BODY WITH HIGH CONCENTRATIONS TO THE LEFT SIDE, HE WAS ADMITTED TO THE SALINE COUNTY MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN BENTON, AR.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE WAS TREATED FOR MINOR ABRASIONS AT THE SAME HOSPITAL AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY, EARLY MORNING.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE RECEIVED A TRAFFIC CITATION FOR CROSSING THE MEDIAN.  THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE BELIEVE THAT MR. RUTLEDGE WAS EITHER SPEEDING OR SLEEPING AT THE WHEEL UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, THE REASONING OF WHICH IS EXPLAINED IN THE BODY OF THE REPORT. ACE CONTACTED SPILLTECH SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE DEBRIS LEFT ON THE ROAD WHICH WAS REDUCED TO A PILE OF BURNT HAZARDOUS WASTE DUE TO THE CHEMICALS WHICH BURNED AND THE AMMUNITIOIN STILL IN THE PILE.  THE ROAD WAS NOT CLEARED TO THROUGH TRAFFIC UNTIL 2:15 PM THE SAME DAY.  ALL PRODUCT WHICH BELONGED TO ACE IN THE TRAILER WAS A TOTAL LOSS, THE EXACT DOLLAR FIGURE WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE ONCE RECEIVED.  THE RYDER TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED.  PHOTOGRAPHS AND VIDEO WERE TAKEN OF THE SCENE AND WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE.

THE OTHER TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS BEING OPERATED BY DON BLALOCK (DRIVER) AND DALE MULKEY (IN SLEEPER) BOTH EMPLOYED BY LEASED DRIVER'S INC. CONTRACTED BY THE ACE PRODUCT BASED OUT OF MAUMELLE, AR.  MR. RUTLEDGE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON INTERSTATE 30 IN BENTON, AR WHEN HE CROSSED THE MEDIAN NEAR MILE MARKER 115.  UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT TIPPED OVER SLIDING ON THE PAVEMENT (DRIVER'S SIDE) INTO THE SOUTHBOUND LANES IOF INTERSTATE 30. WHEN MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT HIT A CURB LOCATED ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE INTERSTATE THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER (FLAT BED) TO BE UPRIGHTED.  THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB AND UPRIGHTING THE UNIT CAUSED A LOAD OF STEEL BEAMS APPROXIMATELY 20' - 30' IN LENGTH TO EJECT FROM THE FLAT BED.  DAN BLALOCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 30 AND ATTEMPTED TO AVOID HITTING THE DEBRIS IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANES BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL AS THE EVENTS DESCRIBED ABOVE TRANSPIRED VERY QUICKLY.  THE FORCE OF IMPACT OR THE DEBRIS ON THE ROAD CAUSED THE FUEL TANK OF THE RYDER TRACTOR TO RUPTURE WHEREBY A FIRE ENSUED.  THE FIRE EVENTUALLY IGNITED FLAMMABLES AND OTHER COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER CAUSING A MASSIVE FIRE.  AMMUNITION AND AEROSOL SPRAY PAINT WAS ALSO IN THE TRAILER CAUSING THESE PRODUCTS TO EXPLODE MAKING IT DIFFICULT FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNITS TO COMBAT AND CONTROL THE SCENE. PHOTOGRAPHS AND VIDEO WERE TAKEN OF THE SCENE AND WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A MAJOR ACCIDENT WHICH OCCURRED IN BENTON, AR AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 AM ON SEPTEMBER 22, 1994.  THE ACCIDENT INVOLVED TWO TRACTOR TRAILER UNITS.  ONE UNIT WAS BEING OPERATED BY A CALVIN RUTLEDGE EMPLOYED BY BUILDERS TRANSPORT BASED OUT OF MEMPHIS, TN.  MR. RUTLEGE WAS HAULING STEEL BEAMS ON A FLAT BED TRAILER.  THE OTHER TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS BEING OPERATED BY DON BLALOCK (DRIVER) AND DALE MULKEY (IN SLEEPER) BOTH EMPLOYED BY LEASED DRIVER'S INC. CONTRACTED BY THE ACE PRODUCT BASED OUT OF MAUMELLE, AR.  MR. RUTLEDGE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON INTERSTATE 30 IN BENTON, AR WHEN HE CROSSED THE MEDIAN NEAR MILE MARKER 115.  UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT TIPPED OVER SLIDING ON THE PAVEMENT (DRIVER'S SIDE) INTO THE SOUTHBOUND LANES IOF INTERSTATE 30. WHEN MR. RUTLEDGE'S UNIT HIT A CURB LOCATED ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE INTERSTATE THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER (FLAT BED) TO BE UPRIGHTED.  THE FORCE OF HITTING THE CURB AND UPRIGHTING THE UNIT CAUSED A LOAD OF STEEL BEAMS APPROXIMATELY 20' - 30' IN LENGTH TO EJECT FROM THE FLAT BED.  DAN BLALOCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 30 AND ATTEMPTED TO AVOID HITTING THE DEBRIS IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANES BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL AS THE EVENTS DESCRIBED ABOVE TRANSPIRED VERY QUICKLY.  THE FORCE OF IMPACT OR THE DEBRIS ON THE ROAD CAUSED THE FUEL TANK OF THE RYDER TRACTOR TO RUPTURE WHEREBY A FIRE ENSUED.  THE FIRE EVENTUALLY IGNITED FLAMMABLES AND OTHER COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER CAUSING A MASSIVE FIRE.  AMMUNITION AND AEROSOL SPRAY PAINT WAS ALSO IN THE TRAILER CAUSING THESE PRODUCTS TO EXPLODE MAKING IT DIFFICULT FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNITS TO COMBAT AND CONTROL THE SCENE.  DAN BLALOCK WAS KILLED IN THE ACCIDENT.  DALE MULKEY RECEIVED A BROKEN SHOULDER AND MASSIVE BRUISES TO HIS ENTIRE BODY WITH HIGH CONCENTRATIONS TO THE LEFT SIDE, HE WAS ADMITTED TO THE SALINE COUNTY MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN BENTON, AR.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE WAS TREATED FOR MINOR ABRASIONS AT THE SAME HOSPITAL AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY, EARLY MORNING.  CALVIN RUTLEDGE RECEIVED A TRAFFIC CITATION FOR CROSSING THE MEDIAN.  THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE BELIEVE THAT MR. RUTLEDGE WAS EITHER SPEEDING OR SLEEPING AT THE WHEEL UPON CROSSING THE MEDIAN, THE REASONING OF WHICH IS EXPLAINED IN THE BODY OF THE REPORT. ACE CONTACTED SPILLTECH SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE DEBRIS LEFT ON THE ROAD WHICH WAS REDUCED TO A PILE OF BURNT HAZARDOUS WASTE DUE TO THE CHEMICALS WHICH BURNED AND THE AMMUNITIOIN STILL IN THE PILE.  THE ROAD WAS NOT CLEARED TO THROUGH TRAFFIC UNTIL 2:15 PM THE SAME DAY.  ALL PRODUCT WHICH BELONGED TO ACE IN THE TRAILER WAS A TOTAL LOSS, THE EXACT DOLLAR FIGURE WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE ONCE RECEIVED.  THE RYDER TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED.  PHOTOGRAPHS AND VIDEO WERE TAKEN OF THE SCENE AND WILL BE ADDED TO THE FILE.
