column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY DANNY NORMAN, RAMP FOREMAN, ITS INTERMODAL FACILITY, THAT A CONTAINER WAS REPORTED LEAKING ALONG DROTT TRACK #5 BY AN OUTSIDE DRIVER WHO WAS TO PICK UP THE CONTAINER FOR DELIVERY. MANAGER COOPER DROVED TO THE UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY AND OBSERVED SEVERAL SMALL DARK LIQUID DRIPS ON THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE UNDER CARRIAGE OF THE CONTAINER, WHERE LIQUID FROM THE CONTENTS HAD WORKED IT'S WAY THROUGH THE WOOD FLOORING OF THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED TO INSPECT THE CONTENTS AND DEVELOP THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED, AND SECURED AT THE DOORS WITH A SINGLE 2X4, WHICH IS NOT ADEQUATE BLOCKING OR BRACING. DUE TO THE LOCATION OF THE LEAK WITHIN THE CONTAINER, AND NOT BEING ABLE TO ACCESS THE AREA, THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO STORAGE LOT #16 AND ISOLATED PENDING CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED RAILBRIDGE, IN COLUMBUS, HOWEVER, WAS ONLY ABLE TO LEAVE A MESSAGE ON AN OFFICE RECORDER. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH K-LINE IN NEWPORT BEACH AND WAS ADVISED THEY WOULD CONTACT THE SHIPPER AND ARRANGE FOR INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER WAS TO MEET A MARINE SURVEYOR FOR K-LINE THE FOLLOWING MORNING, HOWEVER, THE SURVEYOR AND A CONTRACTOR FOR THE SHIPPER SHOWED UP AT 2000 HOURS THE DATE OF THE INCIDENT TO INSPECT THE CONTENTS WITHOUT THE KNOWLEDGE OF MANAGER COOPER. WHILE WAITING FOR THE SURVEYOR TO ARRIVE THE FOLLOWING MORNING, MANAGER COOPER FOUND A CREW FROM UNITED PUMPING SERVICE, CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR FOR THE SHIPPER, WORKING ON THE LEAKING CONTAINER. THEY HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY VLADEK MARCINKOWSKI, MARINE SURVEYOR, WHO WAS UNDER CONTRACT FOR K-LINE, TO ASSESS THE LADING. MR. MARCINKOWSKI AND ART CASTELLANOS, FIELD SUPERVISOR, UNITED PUMPING SERVICE, HAD BEEN IN THE RAILYARD THE PREVIOUS EVENING TO EVALUATE THE LOAD. THE PARENT COMPANY FOR BAERLOCHER USA IS ICC INDUSTRIES, NEW YORK, WHO NEGOTIATED THE REMEDIATION CONTRACT WITH UNITED PUMPING SERVICES. MANAGER COOPER REQUESTED A MSDS ON THE LADING FROM BAERLOCHER, AND UPON RECEIVING A FAX COPY MIDMORNING, FRIDAY, ALSO PRESENTED A COPY TO A CONTRACTOR, WHO WAS WORKING THE LOAD WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE HAZARD COMMUNICATIONS. MIDPOINT INTO THE CONTAINER, A SINGLE 55 GALLON DRUM LOCATED ON THE LOWER STACK, WAS FOUND WITH THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP RUBBED THROUGH. DUE TO THE UNUSUAL CONDITION OF THE REMAINING DRUMS, IT WAS DECIDED TO COMPLETELY OFF LOAD THE ENTIRE CONTENTS. THE CONTRACTOR HAD PLANNED TO OVERPACK THE DAMAGED LEAKING DRUM AND PLACED IT BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER FOR CONTINUATION ONTO THE HARBOR. DUE TO THE LIQUID SATURATING INTO THE WOOD FLOORING OF THE CONTAINER, MANAGER COOPER ADVISED THE CONTRACTOR THAT THE CONTAINER WOULD HAVE TO BE SET ASIDE UNTIL K-LINE ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND MADE A DECISION AS TO REPLACED THE FLOORING OR HAVE THE CONTAINER DESTROYED. CLOSE INSPECTION OF THE DRUMS DEVELOPED NUMEROUS SMALL LEAKS FROM AROUND THE CHIMESS. SEVERAL OTHERS

WHILE INSPECTING TANKCARS IN INBOUND YARD, NORTH LITTLE ROCK TERMINAL, SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL R.L. CARMAN FOUND TANKCAR UTLX 48277 WITH LIQUID ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE TANKCAR COMING FROM THE AREA OF THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. INSPECTION OF THE VACUUM RELIEF FOUND THE BOTTOM O-RING MISSING. SAHM CARMAN WITH ASSISTANCE FROM MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE DOYAL RANKIN, APPLIED A NEW O-RING TO THE BOTTOM OF THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WHICH CORRECTED THE PROBLEM. PAT CONDRY OF ASH GRO CEMENT WAS CONTACTED AND MADE AWARE OF PROBLEM AND CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN.

GARY LEE NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  WEARING MY PPE, I WENT TO ACCESS PACKAGE WITH MY SPILL CART.  I REFERRED TO THE DECISION TREE, WHICH DIRECTED ME TO THE GUIDEBOOK ON LIQUID CORROSIVES.  I NEUTRALIZED THE ACID.  I THEN CHECKED THE PH TAPE FOR THE SECOND TIME TO MAKE SURE IT WAS NEUTRAL.  I THEN DISPOSED OF THE SPILL ACCORDING TO PROPER HAZMAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

I THEN PUT ON MY GLOVES, GOGGLES, APRON AND BOOTS.  I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE AND SPEEDI-DRY TO NEUTRALIZE MATERIAL.  I THEN USED THE DMP TO CLEAN THE MATERIAL.  I CLEANED THE GLOVES, GOGGLES, BOOTS, APPRON, BLADE AND AREA IN GENERAL.  I PACKED THE REMAINING JUGS AND RETURNED IT TO THE SENDER.  THE MATERIAL CLEANED UP WAS DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO PROPER HAZMAT DISPOSAL GUIDELINES.

column168: PITTSBURGH TRUCK ARRIVED 10:50.  BEGAN UNLOADING TRAILER AND DISCOVERED DAMAGED TO FOUR SKIDS OF NON-HAZARDOUS FREIGHT.  REMOVED SUCH AND CONTINUED UNLOADING.  AT NOSE OF TRAILER WAS 6 SKIDS 6.1 DG'S.  UPON REMOVAL OF SECOND SKID, A SEAM RUPTURE WAS NOTED (MIKE KONZELMAN). MOMENTS LATER, MATT ROSS SAID SAME AND EVACUATED WAREHOURS.  IMMEDIATE CALL WAS MADE TO BUREAU OF DG'S.  SENT ALL EXPOSED EMPL0YEES FOR MEDICAL EVALUATION. column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: ON AUGUST 27, 1994 JERRY TURNER, DRIVER FOR CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT DIVISION J.B. HUNT SPECIAL COMMODITIES, INC. LOADED A CLASS 9 LIQUID AT LOCKHEED'S FACILITY LOCATED IN AUSTIN TEXAS.  AFTER LOADED HIS TRAILER WITH A PUMP MOUNTED ON HIS TRACTOR, HE FAILED TO FOLLOW PROPER PROCEDURES FOR SHUTTING OFF THE LOADING PUMP AND UNCOUPLING HIS HOSE.  THE SPILL RESULTED FROM THE NEGLIGENCE OF THE DRIVER IN SHUTTING OFF HIS LOADING PUMP BEFORE EMPTYING THE SUCTION LINE ALLOWING TWO TO THREE GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND.  AFTER THE DRIVER SHUT OFF HIS PUMP, MATERIAL INSIDE THE LINE LEAKED OUT WHEN THE HOSE WAS DISCONNECTED.  THE PROPER PROCEDURE IS: 1. CLOSE THE OUTLET VALVE OF THE TANK WHILE THE PUMP IS STILL RUNNING.  2. DISCONNECT THE SUCTION LINE FROM THE TANK.  3.  ALLOW THE VACCUM OF PUMP TO REMOVE ANY MATERIAL INSIDE THE SUCTION LINE. THEN CLOSE THE INLET VALVE TO THE TANK.  SHUT OFF PUMP.  DRIVER WAS REPRIMANDED AND INSTRUCTED ON THE PROPER PROCEDURES TO FOLLOW TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF SPILL TO HAPPEN.  THE SPILL MATERIAL AND SOIL AND GRAVEL WAS PICKED UP AND PLACED IN METAL DRUMS AND WAS SHIPPED TO ENSCO FOR DISPOSAL.  ALL CONTAMINATION WAS REMOVED AND THERE WAS NO THREAT TO ANY WATERWAY.
RESPONDED TO SPILL IN SORT AISLE WITH MINIMUM PPE. USED DECISION TREE AND LIQUID CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET TO CLEAN UP AND DISPOSE OF.

RESPONDED TO DOOR #103 WITH SPILL CART USING DEC. TREE AND DAMAGE RESPONSE SHEETS. I IDENTIFIED DAMAMGE PACKAGE CONTAINED SPILL AND BROUGHT PACKAGE TO DMP CAGE WHERE I PROCESSED IT, DISPOSED OF, DAMAGE MATERIAL PROPERLY AND RTS UNDAMAGED MATERIAL. IN DIR I NOTED MATERIAL WAS DAMAGED BY SHARP OBJECTS THAT WERE SHIPPED WITHIN THE PACKAGE.
